</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company is an insurance holding company engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through its wholly owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;) and its managing general underwriter subsidiaries (the &quot;MGUs&quot;) that currently specialize in medical stop-loss insurance. &nbsp;Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), which currently owns 48% of AMIC's stock, and IHC's senior management has provided direction to the Company through service agreements between the Company and IHC. &nbsp;Independence American&#146;s primary source of revenue is reinsurance premiums. &nbsp;The majority of these premiums are ceded to Independence American from IHC under long-term reinsurance treaties to cede its gross medical stop-loss premiums written to Independence American. &nbsp;In addition, Independence American assumes full
y insured health and short-term statutory disability benefit product in New York State (&quot;DBL&quot;) premiums from IHC, and assumes medical stop-loss premiums from unaffiliated carriers. &nbsp;Independence American began writing medical stop-loss business in 2006 and will expand this line of business and begin writing two fully insured health products in 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While management considers a wide range of factors in its strategic planning, the overriding consideration is underwriting profitability. &nbsp;Management's assessment of trends in healthcare and in the medical stop-loss market play a significant role in determining whether to expand Independence American's reinsurance participation percentage or the number of programs it reinsures. &nbsp;Since Independence American reinsures a portion of all of the business produced by the MGUs, and since the MGUs are also eligible to earn profit sharing commissions based on the profitability of the business they write, the MGUs also emphasize underwriting profitability. &nbsp;In addition, management focuses on controlling operating costs. &nbsp;By sharing employees with IHC and sharing resources among the MGUs and Independence American, AMIC strives to maximize its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>19</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>The following is a summary of key performance information and events:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Independence American Insurance Company</I></B> </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">2006 was negatively impacted by higher than expected claims from certain of Independence American's medical stop-loss programs. &nbsp;The Company recorded an overall Net Loss Ratio for medical stop-loss of 100.5%, 97.1% and 91.3% in 2006, 2005 and 2004, respectively. &nbsp;The Net Loss Ratio (&quot;Net Loss Ratio&quot;) is defined as insurance benefits, claims and reserves, divided by (premiums earned less underwriting expenses). &nbsp;Based on currently available information, business incepting in 2006, of which a material portion will be earned and recorded in 2007, is projected to achieve a net loss ratio that is meaningfully lower than that of business incepting in 2005, just as the net loss ratio on business incepting in 2005 was meaningfully lower than that of business incepting in 2004.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">Premiums increased 3% to $67.8 million for the year ended December 31, 2006 from $66.1 million for the year ended 2005.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">Added six additional licenses in 2006, bringing total to 43 states and the District of Columbia.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">Average percentage of gross medical stop-loss premiums written ceded from IHC to Independence American increased to 22.2% during 2006 from 21.9% during 2005.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">Of the Company's investment assets, approximately 94.3% was invested in investment grade fixed income securities, resale agreements, and cash and cash equivalents at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;Also at such date, 99.6% of the Company's fixed maturities had the highest NAIC rating designation (NAIC ratings of 1 and 2 designation).</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">In 2006, Independence American began writing medical stop-loss business and will, in 2007, write small group major medical business pursuant to an agreement entered into in 2006 (see Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:51.333px; text-indent:-29.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&#149;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Agreed with a national, career agent marketing organization to begin marketing, in 2007, health plans to individuals and families utilizing Independence American as the carrier.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>MGU Division (IndependenceCare, Marlton, RAS)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">In 2006, the MGUs wrote an aggregate of $94.3 million of annualized gross premium which generated pre-tax income of $1.4 million, as compared to $101.3 million and $4.0 million in 2005, respectively. &nbsp;The MGUs wrote less premiums due, in part, to stricter underwriting guidelines and the continuing generally &quot;soft&quot; market.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Symbol" align=justify><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#183;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><FONT FACE="Arial">In 2006, the MGUs generated revenues of $10.8 million, as compared to $14.4 million in 2005, a decrease of 25%, due to lower volume of premium underwritten and lower profit commissions.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The accounting and reporting policies of the Company conform to U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&quot;GAAP&quot;). The preparation of the Consolidated Financial Statements in conformity with GAAP requires the Company's management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the financial statements and accompanying notes. Actual results could differ from those estimates. A summary of the Company's significant accounting policies and practices is provided in Note 1 of the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8. Management has identified the accounting policies described below as those that, due to the judgments, estimates and assumptions inherent in those policies, are critical to an understanding of the Company's Consolidated Financial Statements and this Management's Discussion and Analysis</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>20</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including legal and other fees, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are estimated in accordance with GAAP. &nbsp;The Company&#146;s estimate of loss reserves represents management&#146;s best estimate of the Company&#146;s liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s policies are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims or open claims from prior periods, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2006. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Medical Stop-Loss</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company&#146;s medical stop-loss business is comprised of employer stop-loss, HMO Reinsurance and Provider Excess.&nbsp; All of the Company&#146;s medical stop-loss policies are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims or open claims from prior periods, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The two &#147;primary&#148; or &#147;key&#148; assumptions underlying the calculation of loss reserves for medical stop-loss business are (i) projected net loss ratio, and (ii) claim development patterns. &nbsp;The projected net loss ratio is set at expected levels consistent with the underlying pricing assumptions (&#147;Projected Net Loss Ratio&#148;). Claim development patterns are set quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history (&#147;Claim Development Patterns&#148;). &nbsp;The Company uses the Projected Net Loss Ratio to establish reserves until developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results and it is feasible to set reserves based on Claim Development Patterns. &nbsp;The Company has concluded that a reasonably likely change in the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption could have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial condition, results of operations, o
r liquidity (&#147;Material Effect&#148;) but a reasonably likely change in the Claim Development Pattern would not have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Projected Net Loss Ratio</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Generally, during the first twelve months of an underwriting year, reserves for medical stop-loss are first set at the Projected Net Loss Ratio, which is set using pricing assumptions developed using completed prior experience trended forward. The Projected Net Loss Ratio is the Company&#146;s best estimate of future performance until such time as developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>While the Company establishes a best estimate of the Projected Net Loss Ratio, actual experience may deviate from this estimate. &nbsp;While the Company believes that larger variations are possible (as was the case with the 2004 and 2005 underwriting years which deviated by 12.5 and 7.1 Net Loss Ratio points, respectively), based on a review of historical Net Loss Ratios experienced by the Company, the reasonably likely deviation from the expected Net Loss Ratio is between three and five Net Loss Ratio points. &nbsp;Therefore, based on its experience to date, it is reasonably likely that the actual experience will fall within a range up to five loss ratio points &nbsp;above or below the expected pricing loss ratio. &nbsp;The impact of these reasonably likely changes at December 31, 2006, would be an increase in net reserves (in the case of a higher ratio) or a decrease in net reserves (in the case of a lower ratio) of up to approximatel
y $1.2 million with a corresponding increase or decrease in the pre-tax expense for insurance benefits, claims and reserves in the 2006 Consolidated Statement of Operations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>21</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Major factors that affect the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption in reserving for medical stop-loss relate to: (i) frequency and severity of claims; (ii) changes in medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, the impact of new medical technology and changes in medical treatment protocols; and (iii) the adherence by the MGUs that produce and administer this business to the Company&#146;s underwriting guidelines.&nbsp; &nbsp;Changes in these underlying factors are what determine the reasonably likely changes in the Projected Net Loss Ratio as discussed above. &nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Claim Development Patterns</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Subsequent to the first twelve months of an underwriting year, the Company&#146;s developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate losses. At this point, claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. &nbsp;Development factors based on historical patterns are applied to paid and reported claims to estimate fully developed claims. Claim Development Patterns are reviewed quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history. The Company must determine whether changes in development represent true indications of emerging experience or are simply due to random claim fluctuations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company also establishes its best estimates of claim development factors to be applied to more developed treaty year experience. &nbsp;While these factors are based on historical Claim Development Patterns, actual claim development may vary from these estimates. &nbsp;The Company does not believe that reasonably likely changes in its actual claim development patterns would have a Material Effect. &nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Predicting ultimate claims and estimating reserves in medical stop-loss is more complex than first dollar medical and disability business due to the &#147;excess of loss&#148; nature of these products with very high deductibles applying to specific claims on any individual claimant and in the aggregate for a given group.&nbsp; The level of these deductibles makes it more difficult to predict the amount and payment pattern of such claims. &nbsp;Fluctuations in results for specific coverage are primarily due to the severity and frequency of individual&nbsp;claims, whereas fluctuations in aggregate coverage are largely attributable to frequency of underlying claims rather than severity. Liabilities for first dollar medical reserves and disability coverages are computed using completion factors and expected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Due to the short-term nature of medical stop-loss, redundancies or deficiencies will typically emerge during the course of the following year rather than over a number of years.&nbsp; For Employer Stop-Loss, as noted above, the Company maintains its reserves based on underlying pricing assumptions until it determines that an adjustment is appropriate based on emerging experience from its MGUs for prior underwriting years.&nbsp; Reserves for HMO Reinsurance and Provider Excess are adjusted on a policy by policy basis.&nbsp; Because of the small number of HMO Reinsurance and Provider Excess policies it writes, the Company is able to evaluate each policy individually for potential liability by reviewing open claims with each HMO or provider group and applying completion factors using historical data.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Fully Insured</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Reserves for fully insured medical and dental business are established using historical claim development patterns. &nbsp;Claim development by number of months elapsed from the incurred month is studied each month and development factors are calculated. &nbsp;These claim development factors are then applied to the amount of claims paid to date for each incurred month to estimate fully complete claims. &nbsp;The difference between fully complete claims and the claims paid to date is the estimated reserve. &nbsp;Total reserves are the sum of the reserves for all incurred months.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The primary assumption in the determination of fully insured reserves is that historical claim development patterns are representative of future claim development patterns. &nbsp;Factors which may affect this assumption include changes in claim payment processing times and procedures, changes in time delay in submission of claims and the incidence of unusually large claims. &nbsp;The reserving analysis includes a review of claim processing statistical measures and large claim early notifications; the potential impact of any changes in these factors are minimal. &nbsp;The time delay in submission of claims tends to be stable over time and not subject to </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>22</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>significant volatility. &nbsp;The Company does not believe that any reasonably likely change in these factors will have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium and MGU Fee Income Revenue Recognition </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. &nbsp;Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American is primarily a reinsurer, and currently derives most of its business from pro rata quota share reinsurance treaties with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life which are wholly owned subsidiaries of IHC. &nbsp;These treaties were entered into in 2002 and terminate on December 31, 2014, unless terminated sooner by Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life must cede at least 15% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American under these treaties. &nbsp;Additionally, Standard Security Life, Madison National Life and Independence American have received regulatory approval to cede up to 30% to Independence American under most of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss programs. For the twelve months ended December 31, 2006 and 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life ceded an average of 22.2% and 21.9%, respectively, of their medical stop-loss business to In
dependence American. Commencing in July 2004, Independence American began reinsuring 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s short-term statutory disability benefit product (&#147;DBL&#148;) business. &nbsp;In 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life began ceding 10% of the majority of its fully insured business to Independence American.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>IHC provides the Company with pro rata quota share reinsurance on business written by Independence American. This business accounted for approximately 2% of the Company&#146;s total earned premiums at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;Commencing in January 2004, Independence American began ceding 30% of its provider excess insurance to Madison National Life. &nbsp;In January 2005, Independence American increased the amount ceded to Madison National Life to 55%. This treaty was entered into on January 1, 2004 and will remain in force for an indefinite period, unless terminated by either party as of any December 31. &nbsp;The Company is not aware of any regulatory or other restrictions on the ability of IHC to fund its obligations under agreements in which IHC reinsures such provider excess business. &nbsp;Any such restrictions would at this point have a minimal impact on the Company. &nbsp;In addition, in 2006 Independ
ence American ceded 50% of its STM business to unrelated reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In assessing the realizability of deferred tax assets, management considers<B> </B>whether it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. The ultimate realization of deferred tax assets is dependent upon the generation of future taxable income during the period in which those temporary differences become deductible. &nbsp;Management considers the scheduled reversal of deferred tax liabilities, projected future taxable income, and tax planning strategies in making this assessment. &nbsp;Management believes that although sufficient uncertainty exists regarding the future realization of deferred tax assets, the valuation allowance has been adjusted to account for the expected utilization of net operating losses against future taxable income.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has net operating loss carryforwards for federal income tax purposes available to reduce future income subject to income taxes. &nbsp;The net operating loss carryforwards expire between 2019 and 2025.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>U.S. Federal and California tax laws impose substantial restrictions on the utilization of net operating loss and credit carryforwards in the event of an &quot;ownership change&quot; for tax purposes, as defined in Section 382 </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>23</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>of the Internal Revenue Code. For tax purposes, an ownership change occurred during 1999 and, as a result, utilization of the net operating losses arising prior to 1999 will be subject to an annual limitation in future years.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investments </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accounts for its investments in debt and equity securities under SFAS No. 115 (&quot;SFAS 115&quot;), Accounting for Certain Investments in Debt and Equity Securities. &nbsp;The Company has classified all of its investments as available-for-sale or trading securities. These investments are carried at fair value based on quoted market prices with unrealized gains and losses reported in either accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in the Consolidated Balance Sheets for available-for-sale securities or as unrealized gains or losses in the Consolidated Statements of Operations for trading securities. &nbsp;The Company also had $4.0 million and $3.6 million, on average, in trading accounts at December 31, 2006 and 2005, respectively. &nbsp;All such trading securities were liquidated at December 31, 2006 and 2005. &nbsp;Net realized gains and losses on investments are computed using the specific identification method and a
re reported in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Declines in value of securities available&#150;for-sale that are judged to be other-than-temporary are determined based on the specific identification method and are reported in the Consolidated Statements of Operations as net realized losses. The factors considered by management in determining when a decline is other than temporary include but are not limited to: &nbsp;the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or industry conditions (including, in the case of fixed maturities, the effect of changes in market interest rates); and the Company's intent and ability to 
hold the security for a period of time sufficient to allow for a recovery in fair value. &nbsp;For securities within the scope of Emerging Issues Task Force Issue 99-20, such as purchased interest-only securities, an impairment loss is recognized when there has been a decrease in expected cash flows combined with a decline in the security's fair value below cost.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles </I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are tested for impairment, on a reporting unit basis, at the end of the third quarter of each fiscal year, or more frequently if indicators arise. The Company defines its reporting units on a segment basis.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company&#146;s other intangible assets consisting of broker/third party relationships are amortized over five years.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Discontinued Operations</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accrued estimates of expected liabilities related to discontinued operations through its eventual discharge. The estimated remaining liabilities related to discontinued operations include contract terminations, litigation and loss from operations subsequent to September 30, 2002. The Company reviews the estimated closure costs liability on a quarterly basis to determine changes in the costs of the discontinued operations activities. &nbsp;The cash flows used in discontinued operations are presented separately in the operating activities section of the statement of cash flows; there were no cash flows associated with investing and financing activities for the years presented for discontinued operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>24</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Results of Operations for the Fiscal Year Ended December 31, 2006, Compared to the Fiscal Year Ended December 31, 2005 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Premiums Earned</U></I><B><I>.</I></B> &nbsp;Premiums earned increased $1,659,000 (3% increase) to $67,777,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $66,118,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;The Company currently reinsures three lines of business from IHC. &nbsp;Premiums relating to medical stop-loss business were $56,179,000 and $57,732,000 for fiscal 2006 and fiscal 2005, respectively. The decline is due to a decrease in <A NAME="OLE_LINK5"></A>gross medical stop-loss premiums written by IHC as a result of stricter underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;Premiums relating to DBL were $3,913,000 and $4,187,000 for fiscal 2006 and fiscal 2005, respectively. &nbsp;The decline is due to a decrease in DBL premiums produced by IHC as a result of a reduction in premium rates. &nbsp;Premiums relating to group major medical and STM were $7,685,000 and $4,199,000 for fiscal 2006 and fiscal 2005, respectively. &nbsp;Independence American began reinsuring 10% of IH
C&#146;s group medical business effective January 1, 2005 and 10% of IHC&#146;s STM in the second half of 2005. &nbsp;The increase is due to an increase in production of these lines at IHC and the lack of STM premiums in the first half of fiscal 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>MGU Fee Income</U></I>. &nbsp;MGU fee income decreased $3,800,000 to $10,356,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $14,156,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;MGU fee income-administration decreased $2,046,000 to $10,238,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $12,284,000 for fiscal 2005, as the MGUs have decreased their volume of business as a result of stricter underwriting guidelines. &nbsp;MGU fee income-profit commission decreased $1,754,000 to $118,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $1,872,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;Profit commissions for a given year are based primarily on the performance of business written during portions of the three preceding years. &nbsp;Therefore, profit commissions for 2006 are based on business written during portions of 2003, 2004 and 2005. &nbsp;Since certain of the MGUs experienced higher loss ratios on those years, profit commissions for 2007 and future fiscal years will continue to be adversely affected.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Investment Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net investment income increased $766,000 to $3,267,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $2,501,000 for fiscal 2005 due to higher yields and an increase in invested assets. &nbsp;The return on investments of the Company was 5.4% for fiscal 2006 and 4.76% for the comparable period in 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Realized Investment Gains</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net realized investment gains decreased $179,000 to $66,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $245,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;The Company's decision as to whether to sell securities is based on management&#146;s ongoing evaluation of investment opportunities and economic market conditions, thus creating fluctuations in realized gains or losses from period to period. &nbsp;Included in fiscal 2006 is an unrealized loss of $96,000 representing an increase in the value of the derivative liability relating to the agreement with EDH (see Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements). &nbsp;For fiscal 2006 and 2005, there were no unrealized losses on securities that the Company deemed to be other than temporary in nature. &nbsp;See Note 6 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Insurance Benefits, Claims and Reserves.</U></I> &nbsp;Insurance benefits claims and reserves increased $3,077,000 to $47,799,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $44,722,000 for fiscal 2005, an increase of 7%. &nbsp;The increase is mainly the result of a Net Loss Ratio of 100.5% for fiscal 2006 versus 97.1% for fiscal 2005 on its medical stop-loss business. &nbsp;The increase in the net loss ratio is primarily related to further development of business incepting in 2005 and 2004. &nbsp;In addition, there was an increase in the volume of group major medical and STM premium assumed from IHC. &nbsp;The increase of $3,077,000 for fiscal 2006 is comprised of a $1,153,000 increase in medical stop-loss expense, a $1,881,000 increase in group major medical and STM expense, and an increase of $43,000 relating to DBL expense. &nbsp;Insurance benefits, claims and reserves for 2006 includes a charge of $1,969,000 to reflect loss development in i
ts medical stop-loss business from prior years. &nbsp;While management sets reserves based on its best estimate of ultimate claim settlement cost, the Company adjusts reserves as claims mature, approach settlement or are otherwise resolved.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Selling, General and Administrative</U></I>. &nbsp;Selling, general and administrative expenses decreased $925,000 to<I> </I>$30,267,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $31,192,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;This decrease is primarily due to lower commission expense of $780,000 incurred by Independence American resulting from a decrease in profit commissions due to non-owned MGUs resulting from higher loss ratios on certain treaties.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>25</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Amortization and Depreciation</U>.</I> &nbsp;Amortization and depreciation expense decreased $411,000 to $689,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $1,100,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;The expense mainly relates to the amortization of the intangible assets for the value of broker/TPA relationships of the MGUs. &nbsp;These assets were part of the purchase price adjustments for the acquisition of IAHC, Marlton, and IndependenceCare-MidAtlantic. &nbsp;Amortization expense for these intangible assets will decline over the useful lives of the assets. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Minority Interest</U></I>. &nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recorded $262,000 for fiscal 2006 and $544,000 for fiscal 2005 of expense related to the 20% minority interest in Marlton. &nbsp;This reduction is due to lower income earned by Marlton.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Income Taxes.</U> &nbsp;</I>The provision for income taxes increased $840,000 to $960,000, an effective rate of 38.9%, for fiscal 2006, compared to $120,000 an effective rate of 2.1%, for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;Net income for fiscal 2006 and 2005 includes a non-cash provision for federal income taxes of $778,000 and $1,785,000 respectively. &nbsp;The effective rate of 38.9% for fiscal 2006 represents a combination of state and federal tax expense. &nbsp;In 2005, the Company further reduced the valuation allowance by $2,079,000 relating to the deferred tax asset, which caused a corresponding increase in such deferred tax asset. The valuation allowance relates to the probability that AMIC might not be able to fully utilize its prior tax year federal net operating loss carryforwards (&quot;NOLs&quot;). &nbsp;AMIC reviews the valuation allowance quarterly to determine the reasonableness of the amount, and previo
usly reduced it in connection with the Company's acquisitions in 2002, 2003 and 2004. &nbsp;Based upon AMIC's profitability in 2005 and projected continuing profitable results, it was management's view that it was appropriate to further reduce the valuation allowance in the fourth quarter of 2005 which resulted in an increase in net income and income from continuing operations. &nbsp;There was no such adjustment in 2004 or 2006. &nbsp;For as long as AMIC utilizes its net operating loss carryforwards, it will not pay any income taxes, except for federal alternative minimum taxes and state income taxes.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Gain/Loss on Discontinued Operations.</U> &nbsp;</I>Loss on discontinued operations, net of tax was $54,000 for fiscal 2006, compared to $59,000 for fiscal 2005. &nbsp;The loss in both years was primarily the result of the re-estimation of lease costs related to the Company&#146;s discontinued Intellicom operation.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;The Company had net income of $1,454,000, or $.17 per share, diluted, for fiscal 2006, compared to $5,460,000, or $.64 per share, diluted, for fiscal 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Results of Operations for the Fiscal Year Ended December 31, 2005, Compared to the Fiscal Year Ended December 31, 2004 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Premiums Earned</U>.</I> Premiums earned increased $5,915,000 to $66,118,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $60,203,000 for fiscal 2004, an increase of 10%. &nbsp;The Company currently reinsures three lines of business from Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;). &nbsp;Total premiums relating to medical stop-loss were $57,732,000 and $57,998,000 for the fiscal years ended December 31, 2005 and 2004, respectively. &nbsp;Premiums relating to DBL were $4,187,000 and $2,205,000 for 2005 and 2004, respectively. &nbsp;Independence American began reinsuring 20% of IHC&#146;s DBL business effective July 1, 2004. Premiums relating to small group major medical were $4,199,000 and $0 for 2005 and 2004, respectively. &nbsp;Independence American began reinsuring 10% of IHC&#146;s small group medical business effective January 1, 2005. &nbsp;Independence American generated $180,000 of STM premiums in 2005, which was the first year in whic
h it wrote such business.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>MGU Fee Income</U></I>. &nbsp;The Company earned $14,156,000 of fee income from its MGUs for fiscal 2005 as compared to $17,597,000 for fiscal 2004, a decrease of $3,441,000. &nbsp;The reduction in fee income is due to lower volume of premiums written and lower profit commissions. &nbsp;Included in fee income is $1,872,000 and $2,749,000 of MGU profit commissions in 2005 and 2004, respectively. &nbsp;Profit commissions for a given year are based primarily on the performance of business written during portions of the two preceding years. &nbsp;Therefore, profit commissions for 2006 will be based on business written during portions of 2004 and 2005. &nbsp;Since certain of the MGUs experienced higher loss ratios in those years, profit commissions for the 2006 fiscal year and future years may be adversely affected.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>26</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><I><U>Net Investment Income</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net investment income increased $210,000 to $2,501,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $2,291,000 for fiscal 2004, due to a higher invested asset base in 2005, partially offset by a slightly lower return on investments. &nbsp;The return on investments of the Company was 4.76% in fiscal 2005 and 5.15% in fiscal 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Realized Investment Gains</U>.</I> &nbsp;Net realized investment gains increased $23,000 to $245,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $222,000 for fiscal 2004. &nbsp;The Company's decision as to whether to sell securities is based on cash flow needs, investment opportunities, and economic market conditions, thus creating fluctuations in realized gains or losses from period to period. &nbsp;See Note 6 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements for additional information.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Insurance Benefits, Claims and Reserves.</U></I> &nbsp;Insurance benefits, claims and reserves amounted to $44,722,000 for fiscal 2005 as compared to $39,173,000 for fiscal 2004, an increase of $5,549,000 or 14%. &nbsp;The increase is mainly due to additional claims relating to increased earned premium volume from Independence American in 2005. &nbsp;Additionally, 2005 was negatively impacted by higher than expected claims from certain of Independence American's 2004 and 2005 medical stop-loss programs. &nbsp;The Company recorded an overall Net Loss Ratio of 95.1% in 2005 versus 90.9% in 2004. &nbsp;Insurance benefits, claims and reserves for 2005 includes a charge of $305,000 to reflect loss development from prior treaty years and a corresponding increase in reserves for the current treaty year. &nbsp;While management sets reserves based on its best estimate of ultimate claim settlement cost, the Company adjusts reserves as claim
s mature, approach settlement or are otherwise resolved.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Selling, General and Administrative</U></I>. &nbsp;Selling, general, and administrative expenses increased $1,564,000 to<I> </I>$31,192,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $29,628,000 for fiscal 2004. The increase is primarily due to commission expense recorded by Independence American. &nbsp;Commission expense for Independence American increased $1,801,000 to $19,954,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $18,153,000 for fiscal 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Amortization and Depreciation</U>.</I> &nbsp;Amortization and depreciation expense decreased $566,000 to $1,100,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to $1,666,000 for fiscal 2004. &nbsp;The expense primarily relates to the amortization of the intangible assets for the value of broker/TPA relationships of the MGUs. These intangible assets were acquired as part of acquisitions made by the Company. &nbsp;Amortization expense for these intangible assets will decline over the useful lives of the assets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Restructuring Expense</U></I>. &nbsp;The Company recognized no restructuring expense for fiscal 2005 and no related expense for fiscal 2004. &nbsp;The Company reversed the remaining reserve of $67,000 related to the restructuring during fiscal 2005. &nbsp;At December 31, 2005 and December 31, 2004, a restructuring accrual of $0 and $300,000, respectively, remained outstanding.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Minority Interest</U></I>. &nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recorded $544,000 for fiscal 2005 and $678,000 for fiscal 2004 of expense related to the 20% minority interest in Marlton. &nbsp;This reduction is due to lower income earned by Marlton.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Income Taxes.</U></I> &nbsp;&nbsp;The income tax expense was $120,000 for fiscal 2005 as compared to a tax expense of $3,569,000 for fiscal 2004, a decrease of $3,449,000. &nbsp;In 2005, the Company further reduced the valuation allowance by $2,079,000 relating to the deferred tax asset, which caused a corresponding increase in such deferred tax asset. The valuation allowance relates to the probability that AMIC might not be able to fully utilize its prior tax year federal net operating loss carryforwards (&quot;NOLs&quot;). &nbsp;AMIC reviews the valuation allowance quarterly to determine the reasonableness of the amount, and previously reduced it in connection with the Company's acquisitions in 2002, 2003 and 2004. &nbsp;Based upon AMIC's profitability in 2005 and projected continuing profitable results, it was management's view that it was appropriate to further reduce the valuation allowance in the fourth quarter of 2005 which
 resulted in an increase in net income and income from continuing operations. &nbsp;There was no such adjustment in 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Gain/Loss on Discontinued Operations.</U> &nbsp;</I>Loss on discontinued operations was $59,000 for fiscal 2005, compared to a gain of $240,000 for fiscal 2004, a decrease of $299,000. &nbsp;The loss in 2005 is primarily due to the </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>27</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>re-estimation of lease expenses related to Intellicom, a discontinued operation. &nbsp;The gain in 2004 is primarily attributable to lower than expected expenses related to Intellicom, MTC, ISP Channel and KCI.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Net Income.</U></I> &nbsp;The Company had net income of $5,460,000, or $.64 per share diluted, for fiscal 2005, compared to net income of $5,904,000, or $.69 per share diluted, for fiscal year 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Independence American</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American principally derives cash flow from: (i) operations; (ii) the receipt of scheduled principal payments on its portfolio of fixed income securities; and (iii) earnings on investments. &nbsp;Such cash flow is partially used to finance liabilities for insurance policy benefits and reinsurance obligations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American maintains a revolving Letter of Credit (&#147;LOC&#148;) with a financial institution to support reinsurance obligations of Independence American in the ordinary course of business. &nbsp;The LOC has an outstanding face amount up to $5,000,000 although Independence American has not drawn upon funds to date. &nbsp;The LOC renews October 15 of each year, unless cancelled by Independence American.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Corporate</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Corporate derives cash flow funds principally from: dividends and tax payments from its subsidiaries and investment income from corporate liquidity. &nbsp;There are no regulatory constraints on the MGUs&#146; ability to dividend to the parent company, however, state insurance laws have provisions relating to the ability of the parent company to use cash generated by Independence American. &nbsp;For the twelve months ended December 31, 2006, the MGUs have paid $4,060,000 in dividends to Corporate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I><U>Cash Flows</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As of December 31, 2006, the Company had $59,155,000 of cash, cash equivalents, and investments net of amounts due to/from brokers compared with $55,720,000 as of December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net cash provided by operating activities of continuing operations for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2006 was $6,565,000. &nbsp;Net cash flows were the result of insurance revenues and fees from MGUs, partially offset by higher than expected claims and losses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net cash used by investing activities of continuing operations for fiscal year ended December 31, 2006 was $11,546,000. &nbsp;This results from purchases of fixed maturities, equity securities, and short-term investments, net of sales of all such securities. &nbsp;Also, in February 2006, Independence American entered into an agreement to write group major medical and medical stop-loss insurance pursuant to which $2,500,000 was paid to EDH (see Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Net cash provided by financing activities for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2006 was $52,000, resulting from the exercise of common stock options.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2006, the Company had $17,646,000 of restricted cash at the MGUs.&nbsp; The amount at the MGUs is directly offset by corresponding liabilities for Premium and Claim Funds Payable of $17,646,000. This asset, in part, represents the premium that is remitted by the insureds and is collected by the MGUs on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent. &nbsp;Each month the premium is remitted to the insurance carriers by the MGUs. &nbsp;Until such remittance is made the collected premium is carried as an asset on the balance sheet of each MGU with a corresponding payable to each insurance carrier. &nbsp;In addition to the premium being held at the MGUs, the MGUs are in possession of cash to pay claims &#147;Claim Funds&#148;. &nbsp;The cash is deposited by each insurance carrier into a bank account that the MGUs can access. &nbsp;The cash is used by the MGUs to pay claims on behalf of the insurance carriers they represent.
&nbsp; The availability of cash enables the MGUs to reimburse claims in a timely manner.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>28</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has $22.5 million of insurance reserves that it expects to pay out of current assets and cash flows from future business. &nbsp;If necessary, the Company could sell its fixed maturity investments if the timing of claim payments associated with our insurance resources does not coincide with future cash flows.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company believes it has sufficient cash to meet its currently anticipated business requirements over the next twelve months including the funding of discontinued operations, working capital requirements, and capital investments. The Company expects continued cash usage for its discontinued operations, which are primarily lease obligations, for the year ending December 31, 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Asset Quality</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The nature and quality of insurance company investments must comply with all applicable insurance statutes and regulations which have been promulgated primarily for the protection of policyholders. &nbsp;Of the aggregate carrying value of the Company's investment assets, approximately 94.3% was invested in investment grade fixed income securities, resale agreements, and cash and cash equivalents at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;Also at such date, 99.6% of the Company's fixed maturities were investment grade. &nbsp;These investments carry less default risk and, therefore, lower interest rates than other types of fixed maturity investments. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006, 0.4% of the carrying value of fixed maturities was invested in diversified non-investment grade fixed income securities. &nbsp;&nbsp;Investments in such securities have different risks than investment grade securities, including greater risk of loss upo
n default, and thinner trading markets. &nbsp;The Company does not have any non-performing fixed maturities.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The composition of the Company's fixed maturities at December 31, 2006, utilizing Standard and Poor's rating categories, was as follows:</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Investment Impairments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company reviews its investments regularly and monitors its investments continually for impairments. For the years ended December 31, 2006 and 2005, the Company had no realized losses for other than temporary impairments. &nbsp;The Company's gross unrealized losses on fixed maturities totaled $1,172,000 and $1,017,000 at December 31, 2006 and 2005 respectively. &nbsp;Substantially all of these securities were investment grade. The unrealized losses have been evaluated in accordance with the Company's policy and were determined to be temporary in nature at December 31, 2006. The Company holds all fixed maturities as available-for-sale and accordingly marks all of its securities to market through accumulated other comprehensive income (loss).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>Balance Sheet</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Total investments increased $8,734,000 to $57,215,000 at December 31, 2006 from $48,481,000 at December 31, 2005, due to net income. &nbsp;The $1,614,000 increase in total stockholders' equity is primarily due to net income of $1,454,000 generated during fiscal 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company had receivables from reinsurers of $12,249,000 at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;Substantially all of the business ceded to such reinsurers is of short duration. &nbsp;All of such receivables are either due from related parties, highly rated companies or are adequately secured. &nbsp;No allowance for doubtful accounts was deemed necessary at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>29</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>CAPITAL RESOURCES</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Due to its strong capital ratio and excellent asset quality and credit-worthiness, the Company remains well positioned to increase or diversify its current activities. It is anticipated that future acquisitions or other expansion of operations will be funded internally from existing capital and surplus and parent company liquidity. In the event additional funds are required, it is expected that they would be borrowed or raised in the public or private capital markets to the extent determined to be necessary or desirable.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In accordance with SFAS No. 115, the Company may carry its portfolio of fixed income securities either as held to maturity (carried at amortized cost), as trading securities (carried at fair value) or as available-for-sale (carried at fair value). &nbsp;The Company has chosen to carry its debt securities as available-for-sale. &nbsp;The Company experienced a change in net unrealized loss of $127,000 reflecting a net unrealized loss of $1,191,000 at December 31, 2006 from a net unrealized loss of $1,064,000 at December 31, 2005. &nbsp;From time to time, as warranted, the Company employs investment strategies to mitigate interest rate and other market exposures.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company enters into a variety of contractual obligations with third-parties in the ordinary course of its operations.&nbsp; These obligations, as of December 31, 2006, are set forth in the table below. &nbsp;However, we do not believe that our cash flow requirements can be fully assessed based upon an analysis of these obligations.&nbsp; Future cash outflows, whether they are contractual obligations or not, also will vary based upon our future needs.&nbsp; Although some outflows are fixed, others depend on future events. &nbsp;The Company has expected contractual obligations relating to non-cancelable leases and insurance reserves of the following at December 31, 2006 (in thousands):</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Under certain circumstances set forth in the Limited Liability Company Agreements of Marlton and Majestic, the Company has the right and/or obligation to purchase some or all of the minority interests in Marlton and Majestic.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B><U>OUTLOOK</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Independence American</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American, which is domiciled in Delaware, is licensed to write property and/or casualty insurance in 43 states and the District of Columbia, and has a B++ (Good) rating from A.M. Best Company, Inc. (&quot;A.M. Best&quot;). An A.M. Best rating is assigned after an extensive quantitative and qualitative evaluation of a company's financial condition and operating performance, and is also based upon factors relevant to policyholders, agents, and intermediaries, and is not directed towards protection of investors. A.M. Best ratings are not recommendations to buy, sell or hold securities of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American is primarily a reinsurer, and currently derives most of its business from pro rata quota share medical stop-loss reinsurance treaties (the &#147;IHC Treaties&#148;) with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life, which are wholly owned subsidiaries of Independence Holding Company (&#147;IHC&#148;). &nbsp;IHC owns 48% of the Company&#146;s common stock. &nbsp;The IHC Treaties were entered into in 2002 and terminate on December 31, 2014, unless terminated sooner by Independence American. &nbsp;There are three factors that determine the amount of premiums assumed by Independence American: (i) the percentage of business ceded to Independence American pursuant to the IHC Treaties or otherwise; (ii) the amount of gross premium produced by the MGU Subsidiaries and other distribution sources written by Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>30</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>ceded to Independence American under the IHC Treaties; and (iii) the amount of gross premium produced by the MGU Subsidiaries and other distribution sources written by carriers other than Standard Security Life or Madison National Life that is ceded to Independence American.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>IHC Treaties</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>With respect to the IHC Treaties, the Company&#146;s operating results are affected by the following factors: (i) the percentage of business ceded to Independence American pursuant to the IHC Treaties; (ii) the amount of gross premium written by Standard Security Life and Madison National Life that can be ceded pursuant to the IHC Treaties; and (iii) the profitability of the business ceded.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Percentage of Business Ceded</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>With respect to medical stop-loss, IHC has agreed to cede a minimum of 15% of its medical stop-loss business to Independence American, and IHC has increased this percentage each year since inception of the IHC Treaties. &nbsp;&nbsp;Standard Security Life, Madison National Life and Independence American have received regulatory approval for Standard Security Life and Madison National Life to cede up to 30% to Independence American under most of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss programs. For the twelve months ended December 31, 2006 and December 30, 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life ceded an average of 22.2% and 21.9%, respectively, of their gross medical stop-loss premiums written to Independence American. &nbsp;This increase in ceding percentage was offset by a decrease in gross medical stop-loss premiums written by IHC (including business written by the MGU Subsidiaries and otherwise) resulting in a small decrease in p
remiums earned by Independence American. &nbsp;In 2006 and beyond, any increase in the percentage of medical stop-loss ceded to Independence American will depend on how much IHC determines it has available to reinsure and Independence American&#146;s desire to increase the percentage. &nbsp;Since the percentage being ceded is now well in excess of the contractual minimum, there is no guaranty that IHC will continue to increase the percentage of business ceded to Independence American or, in fact, cede in excess of 15%. &nbsp;However, the AMIC MGUs are the largest producers of medical stop-loss business for IHC, controlling a majority of this premium in 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Commencing in July 2004, Independence American began reinsuring 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s short-term statutory disability benefit product (&#147;DBL&#148;). &nbsp;Standard Security Life is not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty year. &nbsp;In 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life began ceding 10% of the majority of its fully insured business to Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life are not contractually obligated to continue to cede this business to Independence American after termination of the current treaty years. &nbsp;The Company does not expect the percentage ceded to it from IHC will change significantly in the next twelve months</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Upon renewal of each of the programs underlying the IHC Treaties, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life determine the maximum percentage of risk to be offered to Independence American and Independence American determines the percentage that it wishes to accept. A typical pro rata quota share reinsurance treaty is for a twelve month period in which the ceding company and the reinsurer share the premiums as well as the losses and expenses in an agreed proportion for all policies written with an effective date within this period. &nbsp;Most treaties run from January 1 to December 31, but others could begin and end in other periods. &nbsp;Therefore the percentage ceded could change as the year progresses. &nbsp;If Independence American, Standard Security Life, and Madison National Life had agreed to increase the average percentage ceded to Independence American by 1% (from the 22.2% ceded for the twelve months ended December 31, 
2006) and Standard Security Life&#146;s and Madison National Life&#146;s gross written premium had remained unchanged, Independence American&#146;s premium would have increased by approximately $2.1 million, which is approximately 3.1% of total net premiums earned for the year ended December 31, 2006. That increase in premium, however, would not have flowed directly to pre-tax operating income because of corresponding changes in insurance benefits, claims and reserves and other expenses attributable to the increase in premiums.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>31</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>Amount of Gross Premiums Written</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The gross medical stop-loss premiums written by IHC decreased in 2006 by 4.6% and such premiums produced by the AMIC MGUs decreased by 3.5% in 2006, as a result of writing and/or renewing fewer policies due to competitors' willingness to write business at profit margins lower than those acceptable to the Company, partially offset by increased rates on the policies retained. &nbsp;This resulted in a decrease in the gross amount of premium available to be ceded to Independence American. &nbsp;The AMIC MGUs do not anticipate materially increasing their production of medical stop-loss business in 2007. &nbsp;IHC has reported that it expects its gross DBL premiums to be relatively stable in 2006, however, it expects meaningful growth in its STM and CDHP premiums in 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Profitability</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The medical stop-loss market is generally cyclical in nature. When a product experiences several consecutive years of underwriting profitability, it is not unusual for there to be more competitors entering that line which can increase pressure on pricing and create a &#147;softer&#148; market. The medical stop-loss market began to &#147;soften&#148; in 2003 and less favorable conditions continued through 2004, 2005 and 2006. As a result of these market conditions, the rate that the carriers that cede business to the Company were able to charge for medical stop-loss increased at a lesser rate in recent years, however, increases in medical trend have also been held in check to a greater extent and deductibles and attachment points have increased. This reduces the risk taker&#146;s overall risk exposure. &nbsp;Despite these market conditions, the Company produced significantly profitable results in 2003 and 2004, marginally profitable resu
lts in 2005 and 2006, and expects improved profitability in 2007. &nbsp;Based on currently available information, business incepting in 2006, of which a material portion will be earned and recorded in 2007, is projected to achieve a net loss ratio that is meaningfully lower than that of business incepting in 2005, just as the net loss ratio on business incepting in 2005 was meaningfully lower than that of business incepting in 2004. &nbsp;Fully insured business, including the STM and CDHP lines, tends to be less volatile and less cyclical than excess insurance.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Therefore, the impact on the Company&#146;s operating results relating to the IHC Treaties can be summarized as follows: (i) assuming continuing profitability of the underlying business, the Company&#146;s results would be positively impacted if IHC were to cede a higher percentage and adversely affected if IHC were to cede less; (ii) Independence American&#146;s income would be negatively impacted if IHC&#146;s gross premium written were to decrease, &nbsp;and (iii) Independence American&#146;s income in future years would be positively affected if IHC were to produce higher profit margins, and negatively impacted if loss ratios increase.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><U>Marketing Agreements</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In February 2006, Independence American entered into an agreement with a marketing organization with a growing block of fully insured health business, including CDHPs, primarily sold to small employer groups, and medical stop-loss, to begin writing for Independence American. &nbsp;The organization that produces this business began writing employer medical stop-loss through Independence American in 2006, and will move the majority of its existing block of fully insured and stop-loss health insurance (currently approximately $29 million) to Independence American during 2007. &nbsp;This block, which is expected to have meaningful growth, has averaged 8% risk profit over the past five years, although there is no guaranty that such results will be maintained. &nbsp;Independence American will be the exclusive issuing carrier for business underwritten by this organization through December 31, 2011. &nbsp;Subject to certain conditions, the agre
ement will automatically extend until December 31, 2016, and this organization could be entitled to additional cash consideration (see Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In addition, the Company has entered into an agreement with a national, career agent marketing organization to begin marketing health plans to individuals and families utilizing Independence American as the carrier. &nbsp;The agency projects that it will have $10 million of annualized premiums ($6 million on an earned basis) on Independence American paper as of December 31, 2007. &nbsp;Independence American initially anticipates retaining 50% of the risk on this business. &nbsp;The program will be administered by Insurers Administrative Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC. &nbsp;These amounts are less than what was initially disclosed due to a later than anticipated launch date as a result of product design changes and filing requirements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>32</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:-7.333px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>Item 7A.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:-7.333px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>&nbsp;<I>Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>Risk Management</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company manages interest rate risk by seeking to maintain an investment portfolio with a duration and average life that falls within the band of the duration and average life of the applicable liabilities. Options may be utilized to modify the duration and average life of such assets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The following summarizes the estimated pre-tax change in fair value (based upon hypothetical parallel shifts in the U.S. Treasury yield curve) of the fixed income portfolio assuming immediate changes in interest rates at specified levels at December 31, 2006:</P>
