</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=181.467><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Base scenario</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=29.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=110><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right>42,700&nbsp;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=33><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=100.6><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=181.467><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">100 basis point decline</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=29.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=110><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right>44,831&nbsp;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=33><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=100.6><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right>&nbsp;2,131&nbsp;</P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=top width=181.467><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">200 basis point decline</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=29.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=110><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right>46,960&nbsp;</P>
</TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=33><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=100.6><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right>4,260&nbsp;</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:44px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company monitors its investment portfolio on a continuous basis and believes that the liquidity of the Company will not be adversely affected by its current investments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In the Company's analysis of the asset-liability model, a 100 to 200 basis point change in interest rates on the Company's liabilities would not be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Company. With respect to its investments, the Company employs (from time to time as warranted) investment strategies to mitigate interest rate and other market exposures.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR>

<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>33</P>

</TD></TR>

<TR><TD valign=top width=557.2 colspan=2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=15.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=top width=81.2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>34</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center>&nbsp;<B><U>Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The management of American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot;) is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. AMIC's internal control system was designed to provide reasonable assurance to the Company's management and Board of Directors regarding reliability of financial reporting and the preparation and fair presentation of published financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All internal control systems, no matter how well designed, have inherent limitations. Therefore, even those systems determined to be effective can provide only reasonable assurance with respect to financial statement preparation and presentation. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management assessed the effectiveness of AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) in <I>Internal Control &#150;Integrated Framework</I>. Based on our assessment we concluded that, as of December 31, 2006, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting is effective.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>KPMG LLP, the independent registered public accounting firm that audited the financial statements in this Annual Report, has issued an attestation report on management's assessment of, and the effective operation of, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2006, which is included herein on page 36.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>35</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited management's assessment, included in the accompanying &#147;Report of Management on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting&#148;, that American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries (the &#147;Company&#148;) maintained effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO). The Company's management is responsible for maintaining effective internal control over financial reporting and for its assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on management's assessment and an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting based on our audit.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audit in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether effective internal control over financial reporting was maintained in all material respects. Our audit included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial reporting, evaluating management's assessment, testing and evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of internal control, and performing such other procedures as we considered necessary in the circumstances. We believe that our audit provides a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>A company's internal control over financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;A company's internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (1) pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company; (2) provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the company; and (3) provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timel
y detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the company&#146;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. &nbsp;Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, management's assessment that American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries maintained effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006, is fairly stated, in all material respects, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO). &nbsp;Also, in our opinion, American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries maintained, in all material respects, effective internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>36</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2006 and 2005, and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&#146; equity, and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2006, and our report dated March 15, 2007 expressed an unqualified opinion on those consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>/s/ KPMG LLP</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>New York, New York </P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>March 15, 2007</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:14.467px" align=center><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>37</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:14.467px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B><U>&nbsp;Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>The Board of Directors and Stockholders</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>American Independence Corp.:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries (the &#147;Company&#148;) as of December 31, 2006 and 2005, and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders&#146; equity, and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2006. In connection with our audits of the consolidated financial statements, we have also audited the financial statement schedules listed in the accompanying index. &nbsp;These consolidated financial statements and financial statement schedules are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements and financial statement schedules based on our audits.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). &nbsp;Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. &nbsp;An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. &nbsp;We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2006 and 2005, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2006, in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Also in our opinion, the related financial statement schedules, when considered in relation to the basic consolidated financial statements taken as a whole, present fairly, in all material respects, the information set forth therein.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), the effectiveness of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries&#146; internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006, based on criteria established in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO), and our report dated March 15, 2007 expressed an unqualified opinion on management&#146;s assessment of, and the effective operation of, internal control over financial reporting.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=center><B>American Independence Corp. and Subsidiaries</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:24px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>1.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial"><B>Nature of Business</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>American Independence Corp. (&quot;AMIC&quot; or &quot;the Company&quot;) is a holding company engaged in the insurance and reinsurance business through: a) its wholly owned insurance company, Independence American Insurance Company (&quot;Independence American&quot;); b) its managing general underwriter subsidiaries: IndependenceCare Holdings L.L.C. and its subsidiaries (collectively referred to as &quot;IndependenceCare&quot;); Risk Assessment Strategies, Inc. (&quot;RAS&quot;), and Marlton Risk Group LLC (&quot;Marlton&quot;); and c) its investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (&quot;Majestic&quot;). &nbsp;IndependenceCare, RAS and Marlton are collectively referred to as the &quot;MGU Subsidiaries.&quot;</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Prior to November 14, 2002, the Company (then known as SoftNet Systems, Inc.) was a holding company principally engaged in providing Internet services. &nbsp;Four previously reported business segments, business center services, satellite-based Internet services, cable-based Internet services and document management, have ceased operations or have been sold, and accordingly are reported as discontinued operations (see Note 9 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Since November 2002, AMIC has been affiliated with Independence Holding Company (&quot;IHC&quot;), an insurance holding company, which held 48% of AMIC&#146;s outstanding common stock at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;The senior management of IHC provides direction to the Company through a service agreement between the Company and IHC. &nbsp;IHC has also entered into long-term reinsurance treaties to cede medical stop-loss to the Company. &nbsp;Additionally, the Company began reinsuring IHC&#146;s New York statutory disability business in the third quarter of 2004 and IHC&#146;s short-term medical (&#147;STM&#148;) and consumer-driven group major medical business in 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:24px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>2.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial"><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Principles of Consolidation and Presentation of Financial Statements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The consolidated financial statements have been prepared in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles and include the accounts of AMIC and its consolidated subsidiaries. All intercompany transactions have been eliminated in consolidation. The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect: &nbsp;(i) the reported amounts of assets and liabilities; (ii) the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements; and (iii) the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Reclassifications</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Certain reclassifications have been made to prior years' consolidated financial statements and related notes to the consolidated financial statements in order to conform to the current year presentation.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment in</I></B><I> </I><B><I>Majestic Underwriters LLC</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:61.067px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's investment in Majestic Underwriters LLC (see Note 7 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements) is carried on the equity method with the Company's share of income or loss credited or charged, as appropriate, to net invested income in the Consolidated Statement of Operations with a corresponding charge to the Company's investment account. The </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>43</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Company also reduces its investment account for its proportionate share of the amortization expense for the intangible assets recorded in the acquisition.</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:Arial"><B><I>Goodwill and Other Intangibles </I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite lives, which consist of licenses, are not amortized but are tested for impairment, on a reporting unit basis, at the end of the third quarter of each fiscal year, or more frequently if indicators arise. &nbsp;The Company defines its reporting units on a segment basis.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>For goodwill, if the book value of a reporting unit exceeds its fair value, the implied fair value of goodwill is compared with the carrying amount of goodwill. If the carrying amount of goodwill exceeds the implied fair value, an impairment loss is recorded in an amount equal to that excess.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company's intangible assets consisting of broker/third party relationships and marketing agreements are amortized accordingly (see Note 4 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The carrying amount of the Company's financial instruments, which include cash and cash equivalents, restricted cash, short-term investments, due from reinsurers and premiums receivable approximates their fair values.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Cash, Cash Equivalents and Restricted Cash</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and highly liquid securities with maturities of three months or less from date of purchase. &nbsp;Restricted cash primarily consists of funds held by the MGUs for the benefit of their insurers and reinsurers. &nbsp;These funds are restricted and are to be used to facilitate expeditious payment of approved claims. &nbsp;The funds are replenished by the insurers and reinsurers as claims are paid by the MGUs.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Short-Term Investments</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Investments with original maturities of 91-days to 1 year are considered short-term investments and are carried at cost which approximates fair value.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Securities Purchased Under Agreements to Resell and Securities Sold Under Agreements to Repurchase</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Securities purchased under agreements to resell (&quot;resale agreements&quot;) and securities sold under agreements to repurchase (&quot;repurchase agreements&quot;) are carried at the amounts at which the securities will be subsequently resold or repurchased as specified in the agreements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Investment Securities</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(i)</B> Investments in fixed income securities, redeemable preferred stock equity securities and derivatives (options and options on future contracts) are accounted for as follows:</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:96px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(a)</B> Securities which are held for trading purposes are carried at estimated fair value (&quot;fair value&quot;). &nbsp;Changes in fair value are credited or charged, as appropriate, to <A NAME="OLE_LINK4"></A>net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>44</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; text-indent:96px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>(b)</B> Securities which may or may not be held to maturity (&quot;available-for-sale securities&quot;) are carried at fair value. Unrealized gains or losses are credited or charged, as appropriate, directly to accumulated other comprehensive income (a component of stockholders' equity). Realized gains and losses on sales of available-for-sale securities, and unrealized losses considered to be other than temporary, are credited or charged to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(ii)</B> Financial instruments sold, but not yet purchased, represent obligations to replace borrowed securities that have been sold. &nbsp;Such transactions occur in anticipation of declines in the fair value of the securities. The Company's risk is an increase in the fair value of the securities sold in excess of the consideration received, but that risk is mitigated as a result of relationships to certain securities owned. &nbsp;Unrealized gains or losses on open transactions are credited or charged, as appropriate, to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;While the transaction is open, the Company will also incur an expense for any accrued dividends or interest payable to the lender of the securities. &nbsp;When the transaction is closed, the Company realizes a gain or loss in an amount equal to the difference between the price at which the securities were sold and the cost of replacing
 the borrowed securities. &nbsp;There were no such transactions outstanding at December 31, 2006 and 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iii)</B> Realized gains or losses on sales of securities are determined on the basis of specific identification.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(iv)</B> The Company enters into derivative financial instruments, such as put and call option contracts and options on interest rate futures contracts, to minimize losses on portions of the Company's fixed income portfolio in a rapidly changing interest rate environment. &nbsp;Equity index options are entered into to offset price fluctuations in the equity markets. These derivative financial instruments are all readily marketable and are carried on the Consolidated Balance Sheets at their current fair value with changes in fair value (unrealized gains or losses), credited or charged, as appropriate, to net realized investment gains in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. All realized gains and losses are reflected currently in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;Losses on these instruments were $19,000, $90,000 and $27,000 during 2006, 2005 and 2004, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(v) </B>Fair value is determined by quoted market prices, where available, or by independent pricing services.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>(vi) </B>The Company reviews its investment securities regularly and determines whether other than temporary impairments have occurred. If a decline in fair value is judged by management to be other than temporary, a loss is recognized by a charge to the Consolidated Statements of Operations, establishing a new cost basis for the security. The factors considered by management in its regular review include, but are not limited to: &nbsp;the length of time and extent to which the fair value has been less than cost; the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer; adverse changes in ratings announced by one or more rating agencies; whether the issuer of a debt security has remained current on principal and interest payments; whether the decline in fair value appears to be issuer specific or, alternatively, a reflection of general market or industry conditions (including, in the case of fixed maturities, the effect of chang
es in market interest rates); and the Company's intent and ability to hold the security for a period of time sufficient to allow for a recovery in fair value. &nbsp;For securities within the scope of Emerging Issues Task Force Issue 99-20, such as purchased interest-only securities, an impairment loss is recognized when there has been a decrease in expected cash flows combined with a decline in the security's fair value below cost.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>45</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B><I>Fixed Assets</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Fixed assets are stated at cost net of accumulated depreciation. &nbsp;Improvements are capitalized, while repair and maintenance costs are charged to operations as incurred. &nbsp;Depreciation of property and equipment has been provided on the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the respective assets (3 years for computer equipment and 7 years for furniture and fixtures). &nbsp;Amortization of leasehold improvements has been provided on the straight-line method over the shorter of the lease term or the estimated useful life of the asset.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Premium and MGU Fee Income Revenue Recognition</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Direct and assumed premiums from short-duration contracts are recognized as revenue over the period of the contracts in proportion to the amount of insurance protection provided. &nbsp;The Company records MGU fee income as policy premium payments are earned. &nbsp;MGUs are compensated in two ways. &nbsp;They earn fee income based on the volume of business produced, and collect profit-sharing commissions if such business exceeds certain profitability benchmarks. Profit-sharing commissions are accounted for beginning in the period in which the Company believes they are reasonably estimable, which is typically at the point that claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. Profit-sharing commissions are a function of an MGU attaining certain profitability thresholds and could greatly vary from quarter to quarte
r.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>MGU fee income consisted of the following:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Insurance Reserves </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including legal, other fees, and costs not associated with specific claims but related to the claims payment function, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. &nbsp;These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are in accordance with US generally accepted accounting principles. &nbsp;Many factors could affect these reserves, including economic and social conditions, frequency and severity of claims, medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, and changes in doctrines of legal liability and damage awards in litigation. Therefore, the Company&#146;s reserves are necessarily based on estimates, assumptions and analysis of historical experience. The Compa
ny&#146;s results depend upon the variation between actual claims experience and the assumptions used in determining reserves and pricing products. Reserve assumptions and estimates require significant judgment and, therefore, are inherently uncertain. The Company cannot determine with precision the ultimate amounts that will be paid for actual claims or the timing of those payments. The Company's estimate of loss represents management's estimate of the Company's liability at the balance sheet date.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>46</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company&#146;s contracts are short-duration and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period&#146;s claims, including losses incurred for claims that have not been reported (&#147;IBNR&#148;). Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The two &#147;primary&#148; or &#147;key&#148; assumptions underlying the calculation of loss reserves for medical stop-loss business are (i) projected net loss ratio, and (ii) claim development patterns. &nbsp;The projected net loss ratio is set at expected levels consistent with the underlying pricing assumptions (&#147;Projected Net Loss Ratio&#148;). Claim development patterns are set quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history (&#147;Claim Development Patterns&#148;). &nbsp;The Company uses the Projected Net Loss Ratio to establish reserves until developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results and it is feasible to set reserves based on Claim Development Patterns. &nbsp;The Company has concluded that a reasonably likely change in the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption could have a material effect on the Company&#146;s financial condition, results of operations, o
r liquidity (&#147;Material Effect&#148;) but a reasonably likely change in the Claim Development Pattern would not have a Material Effect.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Projected Net Loss Ratio</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Generally, during the first twelve months of an underwriting year, reserves for medical stop-loss are first set at the Projected Net Loss Ratio, which is set using pricing assumptions developed using completed prior experience trended forward. The Projected Net Loss Ratio is the Company&#146;s best estimate of future performance until such time as developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate results. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Major factors that affect the Projected Net Loss Ratio assumption in reserving for medical stop-loss relate to: (i) frequency and severity of claims; (ii) changes in medical trend resulting from the influences of underlying cost inflation, changes in utilization and demand for medical services, the impact of new medical technology and changes in medical treatment protocols; and (iii) the adherence by the MGUs that produce and administer this business to the Company&#146;s underwriting guidelines.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Claim Development Patterns</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Subsequent to the first twelve months of an underwriting year, the Company&#146;s developing losses provide a better indication of ultimate losses. At this point, claims have developed to a level where Claim Development Patterns can be applied to generate reasonably reliable estimates of ultimate claim levels. &nbsp;Development factors based on historical patterns are applied to paid and reported claims to estimate fully developed claims. Claim Development Patterns are reviewed quarterly as reserve estimates are developed and are based on recent claim development history. The Company must determine whether changes in development represent true indications of emerging experience or are simply due to random claim fluctuations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves for fully insured medical business are established to provide for the liability for incurred but not paid claims. &nbsp;Reserves are calculated using standard actuarial methods and practices.&nbsp; Historical paid claim patterns are reviewed and estimated development factors are applied to immature incurred months to calculate these reserves. &nbsp;The primary assumption in the determination of fully insured reserves is that historical claim development patterns are representative of future claim development patterns. &nbsp;Factors which may affect this assumption include changes in claim payment processing times and procedures, changes in time delay in submission of claims and the incidence of unusually large claims. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>47</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>While these calculations are based on standard methodologies, they are estimates based on historical patterns.&nbsp; To the extent that actual claim payment patterns differ from historical patterns, such estimated reserves may be redundant or inadequate. &nbsp;The effects of such deviations are evaluated by considering claim backlog statistics and reviewing the reasonableness of projected claim ratios.&nbsp; Other factors which may affect the accuracy of reserve estimates include the proportion of large claims which may take longer to adjudicate, changes in billing patterns by providers and changes in claim management practices such as hospital bill audits.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Liabilities for insurance reserves on STM and disability coverages are computed using claim development patterns and projected loss ratios derived from actual historical premium and claim data.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Management believes that the Company's methods of estimating the liabilities for insurance reserves provided appropriate levels of reserves at December 31, 2006 and December 31, 2005. Changes in the Company's reserve estimates are recorded through a charge or credit to its earnings.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Reinsurance</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Amounts recoverable or paid for under reinsurance contracts are included in total assets or total liabilities as due from reinsurers or due to reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Taxes</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company accounts for income taxes under the asset and liability method<I>.</I> Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the future tax consequences attributable to differences between the financial carrying amounts of existing assets and liabilities and their respective tax basis, and operating loss and tax credit carry forwards. &nbsp;Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are expected to be recovered or settled. &nbsp;The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date. Valuation allowances are established when necessary to reduce deferred tax assets where it is more likely than not that the deferred tax asset will not be realized (see Note 13 of Notes to Consolidated Financial S
tatements).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Stock-Based Compensation and Change in Accounting Principle</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On November 14, 2002, the Company adopted certain provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 123, &quot;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&quot; (&quot;SFAS 123&quot;). &nbsp;SFAS 123 established a fair-value-based method of accounting for stock-based compensation plans. &nbsp;Pursuant to the transition provisions of SFAS 123, the Company applied the fair value method of accounting to all option grants issued on or after October 1, 2002. &nbsp;The fair value method was not applied to stock option awards granted prior to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;Such awards continue to be accounted for under the intrinsic value method pursuant to APB 25, except to the extent those prior years' awards are modified subsequent to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006 all such shares accounted for under APB 25 were fully vested or expired. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On January 1, 2006, the Company adopted the provisions of SFAS No. 123 (R), &quot;Share Based Payment&quot;, which requires compensation cost relating to share-based payment transactions to be recognized in the financial statements, based upon the fair value of the instruments issued. &nbsp;SFAS No. 123 (R) covers a wide range of share-based compensation arrangements including share options, restricted stock plans, performance-based awards, share appreciation rights and employee purchase plans. &nbsp;SFAS No. 123 (R) replaces SFAS No. 123. &nbsp;In March 2005, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) issued Staff Accounting Bulletin No. 107 (SAB 107) </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>48</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>regarding the SEC's interpretation of SFAS No. 123 (R) and the valuation of share-based payments for public companies. The company has applied the provisions of SAB 107 in its adoption of SFAS No. 123 (R) and accordingly recorded share-based payment expense in selling, general and administrative expenses. &nbsp;Since the Company previously adopted the provisions of SFAS No. 123, effective November 14, 2002, the adoption of SFAS No. 123 (R) did not have a material impact on the Company's Consolidated Financial Statements.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Income Per Common Share</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Basic income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Diluted income per common share is computed using the weighted average number of common stock shares and common stock equivalent shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;Common stock equivalents consist of stock options (using the &quot;treasury stock&quot; method). &nbsp;Common Stock equivalent shares are excluded from the computation if the effect is anti-dilutive. &nbsp;As a result of the anti-dilutive effect, common stock equivalent shares have been excluded from the computation of diluted earnings per share for periods presented with a net loss. &nbsp;Included in the diluted earnings per share calculation for fiscal years 2006, 2005 and 2004, are 54,000, 79,000 and 101,000 shares, respectively, from the assumed exercise of options using the treasury stock method. &nbs
p;Net income does not change as a result of the assumed dilution of options.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Recent Accounting Pronouncements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:13.333px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In February 2006, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &quot;FASB&quot;) issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 155, &#147;Accounting for Certain Hybrid Financial Instruments&#148; (&#147;SFAS 155&#148;), which amends Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 133, &#147;Accounting for Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities&#148; (&#147;SFAS 133&#148;) and Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 140, &#147;Accounting for Transfers and Servicing of Financial Assets and Extinguishments of Liabilities&#148; (&#147;SFAS 140&#148;). &nbsp;SFAS 155 simplifies the accounting for certain derivatives embedded in other financial instruments by allowing them to be accounted for as a whole if the holder elects to account for the whole instrument on a fair value basis. &nbsp;SFAS 155 also clarifies and amends certain other provisions of SFAS 133 and SFAS 140. &nbsp;SFAS 155 is 
effective for all financial instruments acquired, issued or subject to a re-measurement event occurring in fiscal years beginning after September 15, 2006. &nbsp;Adoption of SFAS 155 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:13.333px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In June 2006, the FASB issued Interpretation No. 48, &quot;Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes &#150; An Interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109&quot; (&quot;Interpretation 48&quot;), which prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement attribute for the financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position taken or expected to be taken in a tax return. &nbsp;The recognition threshold is based on a determination of whether it is more likely than not that a tax position will be sustained upon examination based on the technical merits of the position. &nbsp;Only tax positions that meet the more-likely-than-not recognition threshold at the effective date may be recognized or continue to be recognized upon adoption of Interpretation 48. Interpretation 48 also provides guidance on derecognition, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure and transition
. &nbsp;Interpretation 48 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2006. &nbsp;The cumulative effect of applying the provisions of Interpretation 48 is reported as an adjustment to retained earnings as of the beginning of the year of adoption. &nbsp;The amount of the cumulative-effect adjustment is the difference between the net amount of assets and liabilities recognized in the balance sheet prior to the application of Interpretation 48 and the net amount of assets and liabilities recognized as a result of applying Interpretation 48. &nbsp;Adoption of Interpretation 48 on January 1, 2007 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company's consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:13.333px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>49</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:13.333px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>In September 2006, the FASB issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 157, &#147;Fair Value Measurements&#148; (&#147;SFAS 157&#148;), which defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. &nbsp;This Statement applies under other accounting pronouncements that require or permit fair value measurements. &nbsp;SFAS 157 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2007, and interim periods within those fiscal years. &nbsp;Adoption of SFAS 157 is not expected to have a material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In September 2006, the staff of the Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;) issued Staff Accounting Bulletin No. 108, &#147;Considering the Effects of Prior Year Misstatements when Quantifying Misstatements in Current Year Financial Statements&#148; (&#147;SAB 108&#148;). &nbsp;SAB 108 provides interpretive guidance on how the effects of the carryover or reversal of prior year misstatements should be considered in quantifying a current year misstatement. &nbsp;The SEC staff believes that registrants should quantify errors using both a balance sheet and an income statement approach and evaluate whether either approach results in quantifying a misstatement that, when all relevant quantitative and qualitative factors are considered, is material. &nbsp;SAB 108 was effective for the year ended December 31, 2006 and did not affect the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>3. &nbsp;Goodwill </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company completed its annual impairment testing of goodwill and an impairment charge was not required.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:51.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Additions of $3,243,000 to intangible assets represent the cash paid of $2,500,000 and a derivative issued to EDH according to terms set forth in Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:normal; margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>5<I>. &nbsp;Marketing Agreements</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On February 22, 2006, AMIC entered into an agreement with Employers Direct Health (&#147;EDH&#148;). &nbsp;Under this agreement, EDH began writing employer medical stop-loss through Independence American in 2006, and will move the majority of its existing block of employer-sponsored group major medical and medical stop-loss to Independence American during 2007. &nbsp;Independence American paid EDH $2,500,000, which EDH simultaneously paid to Independence Holding Company (&#147;IHC&#148;) in consideration of IHC issuing 125,000 shares of IHC common stock (&#147;IHC Stock&#148;) to EDH. &nbsp;The IHC Stock is held in escrow by Independence American until such time as the aggregate annualized premiums written through EDH reaches $30 million. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The EDH Agreement terminates on December 31, 2011; provided, it will automatically be extended to December 31, 2016, subject to satisfaction of certain conditions as to premium volume and profitability. Assuming these conditions are satisfied, EDH would be entitled to up to an additional $2,500,000 depending on the value of the IHC Stock as of December 31, 2011. &nbsp;The Company recorded a derivative liability (&#147;EDH Derivative&#148;) and an intangible asset on its balance sheet in the amount of $743,000 to account for the fair value of such contingent payment at </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>51</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>closing. &nbsp;The value of the EDH Derivative will be evaluated each quarter and the corresponding changes in fair value will be reflected in the Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;If the EDH Agreement is extended to December 31, 2016, subject to satisfaction of certain further conditions as to premium volume and profitability, EDH would be entitled to up to an additional $5,000,000 depending on the value of the IHC Stock as of December 31, 2016. &nbsp;In addition, EDH could be entitled to a $1,000,000 bonus on December 31, 2013 subject to satisfaction of certain conditions as to premium volume and profitability.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company has classified the $2,500,000 payment and $743,000 derivative as an intangible asset that will be amortized over the five year contract period. &nbsp;Such amortization will start in 2007 to coincide with the transfer of business on January 1, 2007.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As part of the agreement, an affiliate of EDH and Independence American agreed to a profit/loss sharing arrangement, whereby Independence American will pay to, or receive from, such affiliate 35% of the underwriting profit or loss of the business written by Independence American. &nbsp;Independence American will receive customary carrier fees on the business written on its paper.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In addition, the Company has entered into an agreement with a national, career agent marketing organization to begin marketing health plans to individuals and families utilizing Independence American as the carrier. &nbsp;The agency projects that it will have $10 million of annualized premiums ($6 million on an earned basis) on Independence American paper as of December 31, 2007. &nbsp;Independence American initially anticipates retaining 50% of the risk on this business. &nbsp;The program will be administered by Insurers Administrative Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of IHC. &nbsp;These amounts are less than what was initially disclosed due to a later than anticipated launch date as a result of product design changes and filing requirements.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>52</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-right:-0.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Government-sponsored enterprise mortgage-backed securities consist of Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation and Federal National Mortgage Association securities.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The amortized cost and fair value of fixed maturities at December 31, 2006 by contractual maturity are shown below. &nbsp;Expected maturities will differ from contractual maturities because borrowers may have the right to call or prepay obligations with or without call or prepayment penalties. &nbsp;The average life of mortgage backed securities is affected by prepayments on the underlying loans and, therefore, is materially shorter than the original stated maturity.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><BR>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Substantially all of the unrealized losses at December 31, 2006 and 2005 relate to investment grade securities and are attributable to changes in market interest rates subsequent to purchase. &nbsp;The Company reviews its investments regularly and monitors its investments for impairments. &nbsp;A total of 31 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 54 securities for 12 months or longer as of December 2006. &nbsp;A total of 52 securities were in a continuous unrealized loss position for less than 12 months and 21 securities for 12 </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>54</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>months or longer as of December 31, 2005. &nbsp;For fixed maturities, there are no securities past due or securities for which the Company currently believes it is not probable that it will collect all amounts due according to the contractual terms of the investment. Based on management's review of the portfolio, which considered the various factors described in Note 2, including the extent and duration of the unrealized losses and the Company's intent and ability to hold securities for a period of time sufficient to allow for a recovery in fair value, the Company did not consider these investments to be other-than-temporarily impaired at December 31, 2006 and 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company had derivative instruments representing the value of the contingent payment due to EDH as of December 31, 2006 (see Note 5 of Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements). &nbsp;There were no derivative instruments as of December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $115,000 and gross losses of $336,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $478,000 and gross losses of $481,000 were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Gross gains of $876,000 and gross losses of $903,000 (including $134,000 from temporary impairment) were realized on sales of available-for-sale securities for the year ended December 31, 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains a securities trading account in addition to its securities classified as available-for-sale. &nbsp;The Company realized net gains from trading securities of $392,000 in 2006, $248,000 in 2005 and $249,000 in 2004. &nbsp;The Company had $4.0 million and $3.6 million, on average, in trading securities during 2006 and 2005, respectively. &nbsp;All such trading securities were liquidated at December 31, 2006 and 2005.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Major categories of net investment income for years 2006, 2005 and 2004 are summarized as follows:</P>

<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>7. &nbsp;Other Long-Term Investments</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2006 and December 31, 2005, the Company had an equity investment in Majestic with a carrying value of $1,009,000 and 1,082,000, respectively. &nbsp;For fiscal years 2006 and 2005, the Company recorded $102,000 and $26,000, respectively, for its share of income from its investment in Majestic.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>9. &nbsp;Discontinued Operations</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Until April 2002, the Company (then known as SoftNet Systems, Inc.) was an Internet service provider. &nbsp;Due to difficult and deteriorating conditions in that market, the Company discontinued this business. &nbsp;In December 2000, the Company's board of directors approved a plan to discontinue the operations of its subsidiary, ISP Channel, Inc., which had provided cable-based Internet access and related services, and the operations of another subsidiary, Aerzone Corporation, which provided Internet and related services at airports. &nbsp;In April 2002, the Company, ceased operations of its remaining operating subsidiary, Intelligent Communications, Inc., following the disposition of its key assets. &nbsp;The operating results of these discontinued operations have been segregated from continuing operations and are reported as a gain or loss from discontinued operations on the consolidated statements of operations. &nbsp;Although it is
 difficult to predict the final results, the gain or loss on disposition from discontinued operations includes management's estimates of costs to wind down the business and costs to settle its outstanding liabilities. &nbsp;The actual results could differ from these estimates. &nbsp;The net liabilities associated with discontinued operations are reflected in net liabilities associated with discontinued operations in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>56</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Intelligent Communications, Inc.</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On March 29, 2002, the Company and its wholly owned subsidiary, Intellicom, entered into an agreement to sell its operating business and certain assets to Loral Cyberstar, Inc. &nbsp;Following the sale of its operating business and certain assets to Loral Cyberstar, Inc., the Company's board of directors unanimously agreed to cease the operations of Intellicom on April 3, 2002. Principally due to the Company's guaranty of Intellicom's lease for its facility in Livermore, California, the Company has reserves for discontinued operations of Intellicom of $555,000 for this liability at December 31, 2006, and $808,000 at December 31, 2005. &nbsp;In October of 2006, the Company entered into an agreement with a third party to sublease the property in Livermore, California for the remaining life of the lease. &nbsp;The income associated with the sublease was previously estimated in the reserve balance. &nbsp;Loss from disposition of discontinue
d operations results from re-estimation of certain expected expenses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Aerzone Corporation</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On January 24, 2000, the Company founded Aerzone (formerly SoftNet Zone, Inc.) to provide high-speed Internet access to global business travelers. &nbsp;As part of the Aerzone business, the Company acquired Laptop Lane, on April 21, 2000. &nbsp;On December 19, 2000, the Company decided to discontinue the Aerzone business in light of significant long-term capital needs and the difficulty of securing the necessary financing because of the current state of the financial markets. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for Aerzone at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of ISP Channel, Inc.</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On December 7, 2000, the Company's board of directors approved a plan to discontinue providing cable-based Internet services through its ISP Channel subsidiary by December 31, 2000, because consolidation in the cable television industry made it difficult for ISP Channel to achieve the economies of scale necessary to provide such services profitably, and the Company was no longer able to bear the costs of maintaining the ISP Channel. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for ISP Channel at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Micrographic Technology Corporation</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As a result of the December 31, 1999 sale of MTC to Global Information Distribution GmbH (&quot;GID&quot;), the Company discontinued operations of MTC. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for MTC at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><I>Discontinued Operations of Kansas Communications, Inc</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>As a result of the February 12, 1999 sale of the assets of the telecommunications segment, KCI, to Convergent Communications Services, Inc., the Company discontinued this segment. &nbsp;The Company has no remaining reserve for KCI at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>57</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>58</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Independence American maintains a revolving Letter of Credit (&#147;LOC&#148;) with a financial institution to support reinsurance obligations of Independence American in the ordinary course of business. &nbsp;The LOC has an outstanding face amount up to $5,000,000 although Independence American has not drawn upon funds to date. &nbsp;The LOC renews October 15 of each year, unless cancelled by Independence American.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Legal Proceedings </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company is involved in legal proceedings and claims which arise in the ordinary course of its businesses. The Company has established reserves that it believes are sufficient given information presently available related to its outstanding legal proceedings and claims. The Company believes the results of pending legal proceedings and claims are not expected to have a material adverse effect on its financial condition or cash flows, although there could be a material effect on its results of operations for a particular period. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>11. &nbsp;Stock Options </B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>1998 Stock Incentive Plan (&quot;1998 Plan&quot;)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Effective October 1, 1998, the Company implemented the 1998 Plan, which the Company's stockholders approved on April 13, 1999. &nbsp;The 1998 Plan provides for the grants of non-statutory and incentive stock options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock awards, performance shares, and other awards to officers, employee and other individuals. &nbsp;Under the terms of the 1998 Plan, stock options have a maximum term of ten years from the date of grant, and have various vesting criteria depending on the grant with most grants vesting 25% on the first year anniversary date of the grant and ratably over the next 36 months. &nbsp;In addition, the number of common stock shares reserved for issuance under the 1998 Plan will automatically increase on the first trading day of each calendar year, beginning in calendar year 2000, by an amount equal to seven percent of the total number of common stock shares outsta
nding on the last trading day of the preceding calendar year, but in no event will any such annual increase exceed 1,333,333 shares, subject to adjustment for subsequent stock splits, stock dividends and similar transactions. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006, a total of 5,966,867 stock shares are reserved for issuance under the 1998 Plan. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006, stock options for 491,500 common stock shares were outstanding, stock options for 425,999 common stock shares were vested, and 5,411,893 common stock shares remained available for future stock options grants and other awards. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>

</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>60</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always"><B><I>Stock-Based Compensation and Change in Accounting Principle </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On November 14, 2002, the Company adopted certain provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 123, &quot;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&quot; (&quot;SFAS 123&quot;). &nbsp;SFAS 123 established a fair-value-based method of accounting for stock-based compensation plans. &nbsp;Pursuant to the transition provisions of SFAS 123, the Company applied the fair value method of accounting to all option grants issued on or after October 1, 2002. &nbsp;The fair value method was not applied to stock option awards granted prior to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;Such awards continue to be accounted for under the intrinsic value method pursuant to APB 25, except to the extent those prior years' awards are modified subsequent to October 1, 2002. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006 all such shares accounted for under APB 25 were fully vested or expired. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>On January 1, 2006, the Company adopted the provisions of SFAS No. 123 (R), &quot;Share Based Payment&quot;, which requires compensation cost relating to share-based payment transactions to be recognized in the financial statements, based upon the fair value of the instruments issued. &nbsp;SFAS No. 123 (R) covers a wide range of share-based compensation arrangements including share options, restricted stock plans, performance-based awards, share appreciation rights and employee purchase plans. &nbsp;SFAS No. 123 (R) replaces SFAS No. 123, which established as preferable a fair value based method of accounting for share-based compensation with employees, but permitted the option of continuing to apply the guidance of APB Opinion No. 25, as long as the notes to the financial statements disclosed the effects of the preferable fair value method. &nbsp;In March 2005, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) issued Staff Accounting Bulle
tin No. 107 (SAB 107) regarding the SEC's interpretation of SFAS No. 123 (R) and the valuation of share-based payments for public companies. The company has applied the provisions of SAB 107 in its adoption of SFAS No. 123 (R) and accordingly recorded share-based payment expense in selling, general and administrative expenses. &nbsp;Since the Company previously adopted the provisions of SFAS No. 123, effective November 14, 2002, the adoption of SFAS No. 123 (R) did not have a material impact on the Company's Consolidated Financial Statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Had the Company applied the fair value based method of accounting for stock-based compensation awards issued prior to October 1, 2002, the Company's net income (loss) and income (loss) per share would have been the pro forma amounts as follows (in thousands except per share data):</P>
