<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>12. &nbsp;Related Party Transactions</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American is primarily a reinsurer, and currently derives most of its business from pro rata quota share reinsurance treaties with Standard Security Life and Madison National Life which are wholly owned subsidiaries of IHC. &nbsp;These treaties were entered into in 2002 and terminate on December 31, 2014, unless terminated sooner by Independence American. &nbsp;Standard Security Life and Madison National Life must cede at least 15% of their medical stop-loss business to Independence American under these treaties. &nbsp;Additionally, Standard Security Life, Madison National Life and Independence American have received regulatory approval to cede up to 30% to Independence American under most of IHC&#146;s medical stop-loss programs. For the twelve months ended December 31, 2006 and 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life ceded an average of 22.2% and 21.9%, respectively, of their medical stop-loss business to In
dependence American. Commencing in July 2004, Independence American began reinsuring 20% of Standard Security Life&#146;s short-term statutory disability benefit product (&#147;DBL&#148;) business. &nbsp;In 2005, Standard Security Life and Madison National Life began ceding 10% of the majority of its fully insured business to Independence American.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>IHC provides the Company with pro rata quota share reinsurance on business written by Independence American. This business accounted for approximately 2% of the Company&#146;s total earned premiums at December 31, 2006. &nbsp;Commencing in January 2004, Independence American began ceding 30% of its provider excess insurance to Madison National Life. &nbsp;In January 2005, Independence American increased the amount ceded to Madison National Life to 55%. This treaty was entered into on January 1, 2004 and will remain in force for an indefinite period, unless </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>62</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>terminated by either party as of any December 31. &nbsp;The Company is not aware of any regulatory or other restrictions on the ability of IHC to fund its obligations under agreements in which IHC reinsures such provider excess business. &nbsp;Any such restrictions would at this point have a minimal impact on the Company. &nbsp;In addition, in 2006 Independence American ceded 50% of its STM business to unrelated reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>AMIC and its subsidiaries incurred expense of $622,000, $564,000 and $550,000 for the twelve months ended December 31, 2006, 2005, and 2004 respectively, from its service agreements with IHC and its subsidiaries. &nbsp;These payments reimburse IHC and its subsidiaries, at agreed upon rates including an overhead factor, for management services provided to AMIC and its subsidiaries, including accounting, legal, compliance, underwriting, and claims.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-right:-15.333px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American assumes these premiums from Standard Security Life and Madison National Life, and records related insurance income, expenses, assets and liabilities. &nbsp;Independence American pays administrative fees and commissions to subsidiaries of IHC in connection with fully insured health business written by Independence American. &nbsp;Additionally, the MGU Subsidiaries market, underwrite and provide administrative services (including premium collection, medical management and claims adjudication) for a substantial portion of the medical stop-loss business written by the insurance subsidiaries of IHC and records related income, assets and liabilities in connection with that business. &nbsp;Such related party information is disclosed on the Consolidated Balance Sheets and Consolidated Statements of Operations. &nbsp;The Company also contracts for several types of insurance coverage (e.g. directors 
and officers and professional liability coverage) jointly with IHC. &nbsp;The cost of this coverage is split proportionally between the Company and IHC according to the type of risk and AMIC&#146;s portion is recorded in Selling, General and Administrative Expenses.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-right:-15.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>13. &nbsp;Income Taxes</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Federal income tax provision (benefit) for the periods ending December 31, 2006, 2005 and 2004 include income tax provisions of $792,000, $1,861,000 and $3,155,000, respectively, for the utilization of the Company's Federal net operating loss carryforwards (NOLs). The Company recorded deferred tax benefits on discontinued operations of $29,000, $31,000 and 0 for the periods ending December 31, 2006, 2005 and 2004, which were included in Gain (loss) on Disposition of Discontinued Operations, net of tax, in the Statement of Operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The tax effect of temporary differences that give rise to significant portions of the net deferred tax assets at December 31, 2006 and 2005 are as follows:</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>During the year ended December 31, 2006 the Company increased its valuation allowance by $44,000 representing and increase of deferred tax on unrealized losses allocated to equity. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>64</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify>During the year ended December 31, 2005, the Company reduced its valuation allowance by $1,807,000. &nbsp;This reduction included $2,079,000 for the projected utilization of Federal operating losses which was allocated to operations and a $272,000 increase of deferred tax on unrealized losses allocated to equity.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In assessing the realizability of deferred tax assets, management considers whether it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. The ultimate realization of deferred tax assets is dependent upon the generation of future taxable income during the period in which those temporary differences become deductible. Management considers the scheduled reversal of deferred tax liabilities, projected future taxable income, and tax planning strategies in making this assessment. Management believes that it is more likely than not that the Company will realize the benefits of these net deferred tax assets recorded at December 31, 2006.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2006, the Company had Federal net operating loss carryforwards of approximately $275,811,000 which expire as follows (in thousands).</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>At December 31, 2006, the Company also had net operating loss carryforwards of approximately $25,814,000 for state income tax purposes, primarily in the State of California. &nbsp;Management believes that it is more likely than not that the state tax benefit of these net operating loss carryforwards will not be realized.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>AMIC's ability to utilize its Federal Net Operating Loss Carrryforwards (&quot;NOLs&quot;) would be substantially reduced if AMIC were to undergo an &quot;ownership change&quot; within the meaning of Section 382(g)(1) of the Internal Revenue Code. AMIC will be treated as having had an &quot;ownership change&quot; if there is more than a 50% increase in stock ownership during a three year '&quot;testing period&quot; by &quot;5% stockholders.&quot; &nbsp;In order to reduce the risk of an ownership change, in November 2002, AMIC's stockholders approved an amendment to its Certificate of Incorporation restricting transfers of shares of its common stock that could result in the imposition of limitations on the use, for federal, state and city income tax purposes, of AMIC's carryforwards of net operating losses and certain federal income tax credits. &nbsp;The Certificate of Incorporation generally restricts any person from attempting to sell
, transfer or dispose, or purchase or acquire any AMIC stock, if such transfer would affect the percentage of AMIC stock owned by a 5% stockholder. &nbsp;Any person attempting such a transfer will be required, prior to the date of any proposed transfer, to request in writing that the board of directors review the proposed transfer and authorize or not authorize such proposed transfer. &nbsp;Any transfer attempted to be made in violation of the stock transfer restrictions will be null and void. &nbsp;In the event of an attempted or purported transfer involving a sale or disposition of capital stock in violation of stock transfer restrictions, the transferor shall remain the owner of such shares. &nbsp;Notwithstanding such transfer restrictions, there could be circumstances under which an issuance by AMIC of a significant number of new shares of Common Stock or other new class of equity security having certain characteristics (for example, the right to vote or convert into Common Stock) might result in an owne
rship change under the Code.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>65</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>14. &nbsp;Insurance Reserves</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company maintains loss reserves to cover its estimated liability for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including legal and other fees and a portion of the Company's general expenses, for reported and unreported claims incurred as of the end of each accounting period. These loss reserves are based on actuarial assumptions and are maintained at levels that are in accordance with GAAP. Many factors could affect these reserves, including economic and social conditions, inflation, healthcare costs, changes in doctrines of legal liability and damage awards in litigation. Therefore, the Company's reserves are necessarily based on estimates, assumptions and analysis of historical experience. The Company's results depend upon the variation between actual claims experience and the assumptions used in determining reserves and pricing products. Reserve assumptions and estimates require significant judgment and, therefore, are inherent
ly uncertain. The Company cannot determine with precision the ultimate amounts that will be paid for actual claims or the timing of those payments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Reserves are based on approved actuarial methods, but necessarily include assumptions about expenses, mortality, morbidity, lapse rates and future yield on related investments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>All of the Company's short-duration contracts are generated from our accident and health business, and are accounted for based on actuarial estimates of the amount of loss inherent in that period's claims, including losses incurred for which claims have not been reported. Short-duration contract loss estimates rely on actuarial observations of ultimate loss experience for similar historical events.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The preceding schedule reflects (i) the due and unpaid, (ii) claims in the course of settlement, (iii) estimated incurred but not reported reserves and (iv) the present value of amounts not yet due on claims. The incurred and paid data above reflects all activity for the year. &nbsp;The amount incurred in 2006, 2005 and 2004 for prior years of $1,969,000, $305,000 and $1,730,000, respectively, is primarily a result of re-estimation of unpaid losses on medical stop-loss reserves. &nbsp;This increase (decrease) is generally the result of on-going analysis of recent loss development trends.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:666.267px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>66</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>15. &nbsp;Reinsurance</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Independence American reinsures a portion of its provider excess loss business in order to limit the assumption of disproportionate risks. &nbsp;Amounts not retained are ceded to other companies on an automatic basis. &nbsp;Independence American is contingently liable with respect to reinsurance in the unlikely event that the assuming reinsurers are unable to meet their obligations. &nbsp;The ceding of reinsurance does not discharge the primary liability of the original insurer to the insured. &nbsp;At December 31, 2006, Independence American ceded to three highly rated reinsurers.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The effect of reinsurance on insurance benefits and premiums earned is as follows (in thousands):</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>16. &nbsp;Dividend Restrictions on Insurance Subsidiary</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>Dividends from Independence American to its parent, a subsidiary of AMIC, are subject to the prior notification to the Delaware Insurance Commissioner. &nbsp;If such &nbsp;dividends, together &nbsp;with the fair market<B> </B>value of other dividends or distributions made within the preceding twelve months, exceed the greater of (i) 10% of surplus as regards policyholders as of the preceding December 31 or (ii) net income, not including &nbsp;realized &nbsp;capital &nbsp;gains, for the twelve-month period ending the 31<SUP>st</SUP> day of December next preceding, such dividends may be paid so long as they have not been disapproved by the Delaware Insurance Commissioner within 30 days of its receipt of notice thereof. &nbsp;Independence American did not pay any dividends in 2006, 2005, and 2004.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>

<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B>18. &nbsp;Other Comprehensive Income</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The components of total comprehensive income, net of tax, include net income and certain amounts reported directly in equity, such as the after-tax unrealized gains and losses on investment securities available-for-sale. &nbsp;The components of other comprehensive income for fiscal years 2006, 2005 and 2004 are as follows (in thousands):</P>

</DIV><DIV style="width:586px"><P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>Item 9.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify><B><I>Changes in and Disagreements with Accountants on Accounting and Financial Disclosure</I></B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>None</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial"><B>Item 9A. <I>Controls and Procedures</I> </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>AMIC's Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer supervised and participated in AMIC's evaluation of its disclosure controls and procedures as of the end of the period covered by this report. Disclosure controls and procedures are controls and procedures designed to ensure that information required to be disclosed in AMIC's periodic reports filed or submitted under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, is recorded, processed, summarized and reported within the time periods specified in the Securities and Exchange Commission's rules and forms. Based upon that evaluation, AMIC's Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer concluded that AMIC's disclosure controls and procedures are effective. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>There has been no change in AMIC's internal control over financial reporting during the fourth quarter of 2006 that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, AMIC's internal control over financial reporting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">Management's Report on Internal Control Over Financial Reporting and the Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm can be found in Item 8 of this form 10-K.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Company&#146;s written Code of Business Ethics and Corporate Code of Conduct collectively apply to all of the Company&#146;s directors and employees, including the Company&#146;s executive officers, including, without limitation, the Company&#146;s principal executive officer, principal financial officer, principal accounting officer or controller or persons performing similar functions. The Code of Business Ethics is available on the Company&#146;s website at <FONT FACE="Courier New">www.americanindependencecorp.com/amic/ethics.htm</FONT>. &nbsp;Changes to, or waivers of, the Code of Business Ethics will be disclosed on the same website.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">Re: <U>Binding Letter Agreement</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Dear Peter:</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">This letter (including the attached <U>Annex A</U> hereto, this &#147;<U>Letter Agreement</U>&#148;) sets forth the binding agreement by and among Independence American Insurance Company, a Delaware corporation (&#147;<U>IAIC</U>&#148;), Insurers Administrative Corporation, an Arizona corporation (&#147;<U>IAC</U>&#148;), and Peter W. Nauert, d.b.a. Independent Producers Agency, Inc., a Delaware corporation (&#147;<U>IPA</U>&#148;), with respect to a business relationship (the &#147;<U>Relationship</U>&#148;) in which IPA (along with its agents and representatives) will market and sell certain insurance products to be underwritten by IAIC and administered by IAC, the major business terms of which are set forth on <U>Annex A</U> hereto.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>1.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><B>Definitive Documents and Timing</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">The parties hereto hereby agree to negotiate in good faith and execute such definitive documents (the &#147;<U>Definitive Documents</U>&#148;) incorporating the terms set forth on <U>Annex A</U> hereto as are customary within the insurance industry in connection with business relationships of similar scope and substance to the Relationship. &nbsp;The parties hereto hereby agree to use their commercially reasonable best efforts to execute the Definitive Documents as soon as possible.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>2.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><B>Default Agreement</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">This Letter Agreement constitutes a legally binding and enforceable agreement between the parties hereto with respect to the provisions hereof. &nbsp;In the event that the parties hereto fail to execute the Definitive Documents, and for so long as such Definitive Documents have not been executed, the terms of this Letter Agreement shall be deemed to be the definitive agreements among the parties hereto with respect to the Relationship.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><B>3.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><B>General</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">The laws of the State of Delaware (without giving effect to its conflict of laws principles) will govern all matters arising out of or relating to this Letter Agreement and the transactions it contemplates, including, without limitation, its interpretation, construction, performance and enforcement. &nbsp;If any provision of this Letter Agreement is determined to be invalid, illegal or unenforceable, the remaining provisions of this Letter Agreement shall remain in full force and effect, so long as the essential terms and conditions of this Letter Agreement for each party hereto remain valid, binding and enforceable. &nbsp;This Letter Agreement constitutes the final and entire agreement among the parties hereto with respect to the matters stated herein. &nbsp;The parties hereto may amend this Letter Agreement only by a written agreement of all the parties hereto that identifies itself as an amendment to this Letter Agreeme
nt. &nbsp;The parties hereto may execute this Letter Agreement in multiple counterparts, each of which constitutes an original, and all of which, collectively, constitute only one agreement.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>[Signature page follows]</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><BR>

<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">THE PARTIES HERETO, INTENDING TO BE LEGALLY BOUND, have executed this Letter Agreement as of the date first set forth above.</P>

<P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>2</P>

<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=right><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:672px"><P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>Annex A</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><U>Relationship Terms</U></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:48px; font-family:Arial">Unless otherwise expressly provided, capitalized terms in this Annex A have the meanings given them in the Letter Agreement to which this Annex A is attached.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>1.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Relationship</U>. &nbsp;IPA will market medical insurance products to individuals who are members of the American Small Businesses Association (ASBA). &nbsp;IPA will use its best efforts to cause ASBA to enter into an endorsement and dues collection agreement with IAIC on such terms and conditions as reasonably satisfactory to IAC and IAIC (the &#147;<U>Collection Agreement</U>&#148;). &nbsp;IAIC will underwrite all new policies and certificates arising in connection therewith, and IAC will provide all administrative services arising in connection therewith.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>2.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>2007 Roll-Out</U>. &nbsp;The states in which IPA initially will market such products include: WV, PA, MI, OH, IN, MO, WI, IA, NE, KS and IL (collectively, the &#147;<U>Covered States</U>&#148;).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>3.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Approval of Materials</U>. &nbsp;IAIC will pre-approve any and all marketing materials (including but not limited to brochures, agent scripts and any other materials, electronic or written) and agent training materials, in each case, proposed to be used by IPA in connection with the Relationship.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>4.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Health Coverage and Association Commission Advances</U>. &nbsp;Provided that the Collection Agreement has been entered into: </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial">IAC will advance to IPA&#146;s agents and to IPA&#146;s managers up to 9 months&#146; worth of commissions on submitted (pre-screened, with a mutually agreeable pre-screening guideline) business, comprising both the insurance premiums charged by IAIC and the association fees charged by ASBA, at the same commission percentage and advance percentage, <U>provided</U>: (i) such advances will accrue interest at the rate of 12% annual, compounding, calculated monthly; (ii) the loan agreement executed in connection with each such advance includes IAC and IAIC as third-party beneficiaries with rights of enforcement against the respective borrower and otherwise includes terms reasonably acceptable to IAC and IAIC; (iii) IAC retains the right to discontinue making advances to any agent or manager; (iii) IPA and Mr. Peter Nauert (personally) will, jointly and severally, guarantee the repayment of all such advances and any interest a
ccrued thereto; (iv) an escrow mechanism (at least partially) protecting IAC and IAIC from default risk in connection with such advances shall have been agreed to among the parties hereto.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>5.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Earnings Adjustments</U> &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(i)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial">Determine the combined ratio for each risk attaching calendar year (contract year). &nbsp;Risks attach on their respective anniversary dates.</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(ii)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial">Determine the adjusted target combined ratio, using .95 for all first-year premiums and .92 for all premiums earned in the second year or later. &nbsp;This target will be .95 for the first year since no premium will be second year; it will be a weighted average of .95 and .92 for the second contract year.</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:96px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(iii)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:96px; font-family:Arial">A 100% two-way slide around the adjusted target combined ratio, capped at 2% each way, guaranteed by both IPA and Peter Nauert (personally).</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>6.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Electronic Processing of New Business.</U> &nbsp;The program will include electronic processing of new business. </P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:576px"><P style="line-height:17.333px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:14.667px" align=center>3</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</DIV><DIV style="width:672px"><P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px; page-break-before:always"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>7.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Expenses and Fees by Duration Years &#150; Health Insurance business only</U>. &nbsp;Expenses and fees (by duration year) will be as follows:</P>

<TR><TD valign=bottom width=184.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=141.133><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>Direct Bill</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=83.2><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>$28.00*</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=bottom width=184.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=141.133><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=83.2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=bottom width=184.733><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Provider Access Fee:</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=141.133><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>$8.00</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=83.2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=bottom width=184.733><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Enrollment Fee:</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=141.133><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center>$95.00**</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=83.2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=bottom width=184.733><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=141.133><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=83.2><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD valign=bottom width=409.067 colspan=3><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Renewals rate increases are not commissionable (For IPA agents, smoker loads, and sub-standard rate loads are also not commissionable)</P>
</TD><TD valign=bottom width=144><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD><TD valign=bottom width=66.267><P style="font-size:2pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial">* $10.00 remitted to IPA.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; font-family:Arial">** $55.00 remitted to IPA.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial">IPA will provide to IAC the ASBA fee schedule, which will set forth the gross amount to be charged to the applicant, together with the amounts to be paid by IAC, on behalf of IPA, to ASBA, IAC, other benefit providers and IPA agents. &nbsp;The balance will be remitted to IPA. </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>8.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Due Diligence</U>. &nbsp;IAC&#146;s and IAIC&#146;s representatives will continue their reasonable due diligence review in connection with the Relationship, including, without limitation, with respect to the following matters: agent training, market conduct protocols, procedures and the nature of the Association. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>9.</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>IPA Compensation.</U> &nbsp;IAIC will pay to IPA such percentage of gross commissionable premiums in each duration year as set forth in the above table (in Section 7), less any commission amounts payable to agents. &nbsp;Gross commissionable premiums for this paragraph include smoker loads and sub-standard rate increases. &nbsp;Renewal rate increases are not included in gross commissionable premiums.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial">Additionally, IAC will pay to IPA the applicable portion of the ASBA fees collected by IAC on behalf of IPA. </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>10.</U></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>IAC Compensation</U>. &nbsp;In addition to the administrative fees listed above, IAC shall receive $1.00 per certificate per month in consideration of IAC performing dues billing and collection, commission processing, and advancing on the association dues.</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>11.</U></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Mutual Exclusivity</U>. &nbsp;During the Exclusivity Period (as defined below in this Section 11), IAIC will not underwrite individual, major medical policies on IAIC paper with another agency utilizing primarily captive agents and leads and advances to generate business in the Covered States. &nbsp;In addition, during the Exclusivity Period, IPA will not use a carrier other than IAIC (or its approved affiliate) to underwrite business generated utilizing leads in advance in the Covered States. &nbsp;(IAIC and IAC shall, upon request of IPA, engage in reasonable, good-faith negotiations with IPA with respect to expanding the list of Covered States.)</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:24px; font-family:Arial">For the purposes of this Section 11, &#147;<U>Exclusivity Period</U>&#148; means the period determined as follows:</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:6.667px"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:108px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial; page-break-before:always">(i)</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:108px; font-family:Arial">beginning on the date of the first sale under the program contemplated in this Letter Agreement through 5/31/08; and</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:108px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(ii)</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:108px; font-family:Arial">if, on 5/31/08, IAIC determines in good faith that IPA generated under such program at least $10 million in annualized new premiums during the calendar year ending 3/31/08, through 5/31/09; and</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:108px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(iii)</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:108px; font-family:Arial">if, on 5/31/09, IAIC determines in good faith that IPA generated under such program at least $15 million in annualized new premiums during the calendar year ending 3/31/09, through 5/31/10; and</P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:108px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial">(iv)</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:108px; font-family:Arial">thereafter, as the parties hereto may agree, <U>provided</U> that the parties hereto will enter into good-faith negotiations with respect to extending the Exclusivity Period, at least 60 days in advance of 5/31/10. </P>
<P style="margin-top:13.333px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px; font-family:Arial"><U>12.</U></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px; padding-left:48px; font-family:Arial"><U>Stock Program</U>. &nbsp;The parties hereto will use reasonable best efforts to agree upon a program whereby certain agents will have the opportunity to earn bonuses in the form of stock of American Independence Corp., a Delaware corporation and the parent of IAIC, subject to customary terms and conditions of such a program, including, without limitation, a cap on both (i) the number of such shares any agent may earn during a specified period and (ii) the aggregate number of such shares available under such program.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
</DIV></BODY>

(formerly SoftNet Systems, Inc.) of our reports dated March 15, 2007, with respect to the consolidated balance sheets of American Independence Corp. and subsidiaries as of December 31, 2006 and 2005 and the related consolidated statements of operations, stockholders' equity and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31, 2006, and all related financial statement schedules, management's assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006 and the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting as of December 31, 2006, which reports appear in the December 31, 2006, annual report on Form 10-K of American Independence Corp.</P>

<DESCRIPTION>AMIC 10-K EXH 31.1
<TEXT>
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>To Our Shareholders</TITLE>
<META NAME="author" CONTENT="IHC">
<META NAME="date" CONTENT="03/14/2007">
</HEAD>
<BODY style="line-height:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt; color:#000000">
<DIV style="width:672px"><P style="margin:0px; padding-left:576px; font-family:Arial"><FONT FACE="Arial"><B>Exhibit 31.1 </B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=right><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CERTIFICATION PURSUANT TO RULE 13A-14(a) OR 15D-14(a) OF THE SECURITIES </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934, AS ADOPTED PURSUANT TO SECTION 302 OF THE </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">I, Roy T.K. Thung, certify that: </P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>1. I have reviewed this annual report on Form 10-K of American Independence Corp; </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>2. Based on my knowledge, this report does not contain any untrue statement of a material fact or omit to state a material fact necessary to make the statements made, in light of the circumstances under which such statements were made, not misleading with respect to the period covered by this report; </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>3. Based on my knowledge, the financial statements, and other financial information included in this report, fairly present in all material respects the financial condition, results of operations and cash flows of the registrant as of, and for, the periods presented in this report; </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>4. The registrant's other certifying officer and I are responsible for establishing and maintaining disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e)) and internal control over financial reporting (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and have: </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(a) Designed such disclosure controls and procedures, or caused such disclosure controls and procedures to be designed under our supervision, to ensure that material information relating to the registrant, including its consolidated subsidiaries, is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during the period in which this report is being prepared; </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(b) Designed such internal control over financial reporting, or caused such internal control over financial reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles; </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(c) Evaluated the effectiveness of the registrant's disclosure controls and procedures and presented in this report our conclusions about the effectiveness of the disclosure controls and procedures, as of the end of the period covered by this report based on such evaluation; and </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(d) Disclosed in this report any change in the registrant's internal control over financial reporting that occurred during the registrant's most recent fiscal quarter (the registrant's fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the registrant's internal control over financial reporting; and </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>5. The registrant's other certifying officer and I have disclosed, based on our most recent evaluation of internal control over financial reporting, to the registrant's auditors and the audit committee of the registrant's board of directors (or persons performing the equivalent functions): </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(a) All significant deficiencies and material weaknesses in the design or operation of internal control over financial reporting which are reasonably likely to adversely affect the registrant's ability to record, process, summarize and report financial information; and </P>
<P style="line-height:12.667px; margin:0px; font-family:Arial; font-size:10px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial">(b) Any fraud, whether or not material, that involves management or other employees who have a significant role in the registrant's internal control over financial reporting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Date: March 15, 2007</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<DIV style="width:672px"><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=right><FONT FACE="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><B>Exhibit 31.2 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=right><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CERTIFICATION PURSUANT TO RULE 13A-14(a) OR 15D-14(a) OF THE SECURITIES </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934, AS ADOPTED PURSUANT TO SECTION 302 OF THE </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">I,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Teresa A. Herbert, certify that:</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>1. I have reviewed this annual report on Form 10-K of American Independence Corp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>2. Based on my knowledge, this report does not contain any untrue statement of a material fact or omit to state a material fact necessary to make the statements made, in light of the circumstances under which such statements were made, not misleading with respect to the period covered by this report;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>3. Based on my knowledge, the financial statements, and other financial information included in this report, fairly present in all material respects the financial condition, results of operations and cash flows of the registrant as of, and for, the periods presented in this report;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>4. The registrant's other certifying officer and I are responsible for establishing and maintaining disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e)) and internal control over financial reporting (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and have:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(a) Designed such disclosure controls and procedures, or caused such disclosure controls and procedures to be designed under our supervision, to ensure that material information relating to the registrant, including its consolidated subsidiaries, is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during the period in which this report is being prepared;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(b) Designed such internal control over financial reporting, or caused such internal control over financial reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(c) Evaluated the effectiveness of the registrant's disclosure controls and procedures and presented in this report our conclusions about the effectiveness of the disclosure controls and procedures, as of the end of the period covered by this report based on such evaluation; and</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(d) Disclosed in this report any change in the registrant's internal control over financial reporting that occurred during the registrant's most recent fiscal quarter (the registrant's fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the registrant's internal control over financial reporting; and</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>5. The registrant's other certifying officer and I have disclosed, based on our most recent evaluation of internal control over financial reporting, to the registrant's auditors and the audit committee of the registrant's board of directors (or persons performing the equivalent functions):</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:32.6px; text-indent:32.667px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(a) All significant deficiencies and material weaknesses in the design or operation of internal control over financial reporting which are reasonably likely to adversely affect the registrant's ability to record, process, summarize and report financial information; and</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:66px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(b) Any fraud, whether or not material, that involves management or other employees who have a significant role in the registrant's internal control over financial reporting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial">Date: March 15, 2007</P>

<DIV style="width:672px"><P style="line-height:normal; margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; font-family:Arial; font-size:16px" align=right><FONT FACE="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><B>Exhibit 32.1</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CERTIFICATION PURSUANT TO </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>18 U.S.C. SECTION 1350, </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>AS ADOPTED PURSUANT TO </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>SECTION 906 OF THE SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:37.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In connection with the Annual Report of American Independence Corp. (the &quot;Company&quot;) on Form 10-K for the period ending December 31, 2006 as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on the date hereof (the &quot;Report&quot;), I, Roy T. K. Thung, Chief Executive Officer of the Company, certify, pursuant to 18 U.S.C. ss. 1350, as adopted pursuant to ss. 906 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, that to my knowledge:</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:-9.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(1</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:49.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The Report fully complies with the requirements of section&nbsp;13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934; and </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:-9.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>(2)</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:49.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>The information contained in the Report fairly presents, in all material respects, the financial condition and results of operations of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

<DIV style="width:672px"><P style="margin:0px; padding-left:576px; font-family:Arial"><FONT FACE="Arial"><B>Exhibit&nbsp;32.2 </B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=right><BR></P>
<A NAME="a2129092zex_32_2_htm_kw2502_internationa"></A><A NAME="a2129092zex_32_2_htm_toc_kw2502_2"></A><P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>CERTIFICATION PURSUANT TO </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>18 U.S.C. SECTION 1350, </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>AS ADOPTED PURSUANT TO </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Arial" align=center><B>SECTION 906 OF THE SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002 </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:37.333px; font-family:Arial" align=justify>In connection with the Annual Report of American Independence Corp. (the &quot;Company&quot;) on Form&nbsp;10-K for the period ending December&nbsp;31, 2006 as filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission on the date hereof (the &quot;Report&quot;), I, Teresa A. Herbert Vice President, Chief Financial Officer of the Company, certify, pursuant to 18&nbsp;U.S.C. ss. 1350, as adopted pursuant to ss. 906 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, that to my knowledge:</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:-9.333px; font-family:Arial">(1) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Report fully complies with the requirements of section&nbsp;13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934; and </P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:46.667px; text-indent:-9.333px; font-family:Arial">(2) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The information contained in the Report fairly presents, in all material respects, the financial condition and results of operations of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
